metadata.title: Textile, apparel, leather production machinery— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Special process machinery and equipment which are primarily employed in the textile, apparel, and leather production that are specified but do not meet descriptions of codes 3661 through 3665.

metadata.title: Separating and conversion machinery
metadata.definition: This source group classifies machinery and equipment which perform pressurizing, separating, and material and energy conversion tasks. They are often used in oil and gas processing and refining.
metadata.includes: Centrifuges; distilling and rectifying machinery; dyeing machinery other than for textiles; gas liquefying machinery; paint mixing machinery; painting, priming, metal coating machinery; pumps, except air compressor

metadata.title: Separating and conversion— unspecified
metadata.definition: Machinery and equipment which perform pressurizing, separating, and material and energy conversion tasks where a more specific code from 3671 to 3679 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Centrifuges
metadata.definition: Machines that apply centrifugal force to its contents via rapid rotation in order to separate substances, such as fluids of different densities.
metadata.includes: Sand separator (oil and gas)

metadata.title: Distilling, rectifying machinery
metadata.definition: Machines that separate substances from dilutants or impurities by means of heating the source material to a vapor and then, condensing it back to a liquid, and collecting the distilled substance.

metadata.title: Filtering and sequestration machinery
metadata.definition: Machines that separate suspended solid matter from a liquids or air, by causing them to pass through a filtering medium to trap the solid particles while allowing the liquid or air to pass through.
metadata.includes: Wastewater filtration systems; gas sequestration machinery

metadata.title: Liquefaction machinery
metadata.definition: Machines that turn gases into liquids. It is often applied to convert gases that do not exist naturally in liquid form.
metadata.includes: Gas liquefying equipment; fluidization machinery

metadata.title: Generators
metadata.definition: Devices that convert mechanical, fuel, or other energy into electricity.
metadata.includes: Gas generators; alternators; rotors; staters

metadata.title: Separating and conversion machinery— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Machinery and equipment which perform pressurizing, separating, and material and energy conversion tasks that are specified but do not meet descriptions of codes 3671 through 3675.
metadata.includes: Particle accelerators

metadata.title: Other special process machinery

metadata.includes: Product-vibrating machinery; diagnostic machinery
metadata.excludes: Hospital diagnostic machinery (362); mineral property analyzers (324)

metadata.title: Other special process machinery— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Other special process machinery that are specified but do not meet descriptions of codes 3610 through 3691.
metadata.includes: Dyeing machinery, except textile

metadata.title: Flying and orbiting machinery
metadata.definition: This major group classifies machinery that is designed to fly or orbit the earth in order to perform a range of tasks, including transportation of goods, communication, and information gathering.

metadata.title: Flying and orbiting machinery— unspecified
metadata.definition: Machinery that is designed to fly or orbit the earth where a more specific code from 371 to 379 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Rockets— unmanned
metadata.definition: Cylindrical machines are propelled at great speeds to pass beyond the earth's atmosphere via the combustion of its contents. They are used for transport of goods such as satellites. They may also be able to reenter the atmosphere and land.
metadata.includes: Single use rockets; multiple use rockets

metadata.title: Satellites
metadata.definition: Machines that are placed in orbit around the earth or other celestial body in order to collect information or for communication.
metadata.includes: Communications satellite; remote sensing satellite; navigation satellite

metadata.title: Drones
metadata.definition: Autonomous and remote operated flying machines equipped to perform a variety of aerial functions, from item delivery to site inspections.
metadata.includes: Multi-rotor; single-rotor; fixed wing; surveillance and surveying drones; delivery drones; filming drones

metadata.title: Flying and orbiting machinery— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Machinery that is designed to fly or orbit the earth that are specified but do not meet descriptions of codes 371 through 373.

metadata.title: Miscellaneous machinery
metadata.definition: This major group includes machines that do not meet the descriptions of major groups 31 through 38.
metadata.excludes: Road line marking machinery (3269); paper coating machinery (3642);  air compressor pumps (345); office machinery and equipment (754)

metadata.title: Vending, and gaming machines
metadata.definition: Machines that are operated by coins, small bills or bank card to dispense individual food and beverages or other merchandise. It also includes pay per play gaming machines.
metadata.includes: Arcade games, arcade cabinets;  slot machines; casino game machines; food vending machines; hot and cold beverage vending machines; merchandise vending machine; candy dispensing machines

metadata.title: Ski lifts, gondola rides
metadata.definition: Amusement-type rides that consist of a cabin that moves suspended along a cable.
metadata.includes: Chair lift; J-bar lift; T-bar lift; ski tow; aerial gondola rides (regardless of venue); zip lines

metadata.title: Other amusement rides
metadata.definition: All types of rides used for entertainment and amusement purposes.
metadata.includes: Spinning amusement rides, Ferris wheels; roller coaster

metadata.title: Other miscellaneous machinery— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Other types of machinery that are specified but do not meet descriptions of codes 391 through 393.

metadata.title: PARTS AND MATERIALS
metadata.definition: This division classifies machine parts, tool parts, and automobile parts, as well as building materials, insulating materials, and nonstructural metal materials. Many of the parts and materials classified here are the smaller components of larger machines, tools, vehicles, buildings, etc. In most instances, detailed codes for "parts" are provided for those parts expected to be sources of injury independent of the "whole" machine, tool, vehicle, building, or other object. If a part is attached to a machine, tool, or vehicle, then the entire machine, tool, or vehicle should be listed as the source, unless the event is overexertion or the injury was inflicted by an electrical cord, overhead powerline, or floor of a vehicle in a non-transportation incident. If a part is known to be unattached and independent of a machine, tool, or vehicle—or if it is probable that a machine, tool, or vehicle is not involved in the injury—then that specific part should be listed as the source. If the material identified as the source of an injury is the general floor surface in a building or on the ground, then the appropriate structure or surface in Division 6 (Structures and Surfaces) should be listed as the source. If the material identified as the source of an injury is an independent, unattached element, then that specific element (part or material) should be listed as the source.
metadata.includes: Building materials—solid elements; structural metal materials; fasteners, connectors, ropes, ties; hoisting accessories; machine, tool, and electric parts; metal materials—nonstructural; tars, sealants, caulking, insulating material; tarps and sheeting—nonmetal; vehicle and mobile equipment parts
metadata.excludes: Chemicals and chemical products (1); containers (2); hoses (2124); furniture and fixtures (22); lighting fixtures (224) and plumbing fixtures (225); machinery (3); structural elements (65); vehicles (8); apparel and textiles (91); paper, sheets (932); slinters, particles (942)

metadata.title: Parts and materials— unspecified

metadata.title: Beams, rods, blocks—plastic
metadata.definition: Unattached blocks, typically made of recycled plastic, primarily used in the construction of buildings, surfaces, and other structures.
metadata.includes: Recycled plastic blocks

metadata.title: Beams, rods, blocks—fiberglass
metadata.definition: Unattached fiberglass rods and beams, primarily used in the construction of buildings, surfaces, and other structures.

metadata.title: Rods, reinforcing bar (rebar)—metal
metadata.definition: Unattached rods and reinforcing bars (rebar) primarily used in the construction of buildings, surfaces, and other structures.

metadata.title: Dowls, rods, stakes—wooden
metadata.definition: Unattached wooden dowls, rods and stakes primarily used in the construction of buildings, surfaces, and other structures.
metadata.includes: Shims; spindles

metadata.title: Multiple beams, rods, blocks
metadata.definition: Unattached beams, rods or blocks where more than one type of material from codes 4211 through 4219 are involved.
metadata.excludes: pallets of materials (217); bundles of materials (2141)

metadata.title: Beams, rods, blocks— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Unattached materials in the form of beams, rods and blocks where the specified material does not match descriptions of codes 4211 through 4218.

metadata.title: Pipes, ducts, tubing
metadata.definition: This source group consists of individual, unattached sections of pipes, ducts, and tubing which are primarily used in the construction of buildings and other structures which require water, gas, electricity, or ventilation. Codes from this group do not pertain to quantities of building materials grouped into containers, packages, or bundles. They must also be unattached to or separated from a structure.
metadata.excludes: Hoses and pressure lines are classified in major group (212) (Containers—pressurized). Pipe and tubing bundles (Division 2); Building systems (64); Oil and gas pipeline (6123); Sewers, drains, water pipes (6122)

metadata.title: Pipes, ducts, tubing— unspecified
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of pipes, ducts, and tubing where a more specific code from 4221 to 4229 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Pipes and tubes— wooden
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of pipe and tubing made of wood.
metadata.includes: Bamboo used for piping
metadata.excludes: Pipe and tubing bundles (Division 2); Building systems (64)

metadata.title: Pipes, conduits— concrete or clay
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of pipe and tubing made of concrete or clay. Typically used in large sewer and drain lines.

metadata.title: Pipes, tubes— metal
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of pipe and tubing made of metal which may be used for water or gas lines, or for machinery.
metadata.includes: Tubulars; steel and iron pipes; copper pipes
metadata.excludes: Pressurized pipes (212); Pipe and tubing bundles (Division 2); Building systems (64); Oil and gas pipeline (6123); Sewers, drains, water pipes (6122)

metadata.title: Pipes and tubes— plastic, PVC, rubber
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of pipe and tubing typically used for building plumbing.
metadata.excludes: Pipe and tubing bundles (Division 2); building plumbing systems (642)

metadata.title: Pipes and tubes— fiberglass
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of fiberglass or other epoxied fibers pipe and tubing typically used in larger water line and drain line projects, including sewer relining.
metadata.includes: Sewer pipe reliners-epoxy and fiberglass
metadata.excludes: Oil and gas pipeline (6123); sewers, drains, water pipes (6122); building systems (64)

metadata.title: Ducts— any material
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of tubes or passageways, typically used in a building for promoting air circulation ventilation.
metadata.includes: Residential and commercial metal ducts; flexible ventilation hoses; dryer vents

metadata.title: Gutters, downspouts— any material
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of gutter, used to divert rain water from the roof of a building.

metadata.title: Multiple pipes, ducts, tubing
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of pipes, ducts, and tubing where more than one type of material from codes 4221 through 4229 are involved.
metadata.excludes: Oil and gas pipeline (6123); sewers, drains, water pipes (6122); building systems (64); bundles of materials (2141)

metadata.title: Pipes, ducts, tubing— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of pipes, ducts, and tubing where the specified material does not match descriptions of codes 4221 through 4228.

metadata.title: Structural panels, sheets, plates
metadata.definition: This source group consists of individual, unattached panels, sheets and slabs. These are broad, flat pieces of material used in the used in the construction of buildings and other structures. Codes from this group do not pertain to quantities of building materials grouped into containers, packages, or bundles. They must also be unattached to or separated from a structure.
metadata.excludes: Pallets of materials (217); bundles of materials (2141)

metadata.title: Structural panels and sheets— unspecified
metadata.definition: Unattached panels, sheets and slabs where a more specific code from 4231 through 4239 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Sheets, panels— wood, plywood, MDF
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of wooden panels or plywood which may be used for a variety of purposes in the construction of buildings and structures.
metadata.includes: Medium density particle board (MDF)
metadata.excludes: Pallets of materials (217); bundles of materials (2141); walls- structurally attached (655)

metadata.title: Plates, slabs— concrete and stone
metadata.definition: Unattached slabs of concrete or stone which may be used for a variety of purposes in the construction of buildings and structures.
metadata.includes: Stone counter slabs; concrete slabs

metadata.title: Panels, sheets, plates— metal
metadata.definition: Unattached metal plates, panels and sheets which may be used for a variety of purposes in the construction of buildings, roads, as well as other applications.
metadata.includes: Metal grates

metadata.title: Panels, sheets, plates— acrylic, plexiglass
metadata.definition: Unattached acrylic and plexiglass panels which may be used for a variety of purposes.
metadata.includes: Floor panels; window panels
metadata.excludes: Windows— part of structure (652); vehicle windshields (4724)

metadata.title: Panels, sheets, plates— glass
metadata.definition: Unattached panes and sheets of glass which may be used for a variety of purposes in construction or other applications
metadata.includes: Picture frame glass; table protectors; window panes
metadata.excludes: Windows— part of structure (652); vehicle windshields (4724)

metadata.title: Wallboard, drywall, sheetrock
metadata.definition: Unattached wallboard, drywall, or sheetrock which is typically used for interior walls in the construction of buildings and structures.
metadata.excludes: Pallets of materials (217); bundles of materials (2141); walls- structurally attached (655)

metadata.title: Multiple structural panel and sheet materials
metadata.definition: Unattached panels, sheets and slabs where more than one type of material from codes 4231 through 4239 are involved.
metadata.excludes: Pallets of materials (217); bundles of materials (2141); structures (63); buildings (62)

metadata.title: Structural panels and sheets— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Unattached panels, sheets and slabs where the specified material does not match descriptions of codes 4231 through 4238.
metadata.includes: Prefabricated wood and PVC fencing panels
metadata.excludes: Fences (6334); gates (6335); Wire and mesh fencing and screening material

metadata.title: Finishing and surfacing materials
metadata.definition: This source group consists of individual, unattached materials that are used for surfacing and finishing the interiors and exteriors buildings, structures and ground surfaces. Codes from this group do not pertain to quantities of building materials grouped into containers, packages, or bundles. They must also be unattached to or separated from a structure.
metadata.includes: Panels; shingles; tiles; siding; flooring
metadata.excludes: Pallets of materials (217); bundles of materials (2141); paints, sealants, adhesives (43)

metadata.title: Finishing and surfacing materials— unspecified
metadata.definition: Unattached materials that are used for surfacing and finishing the interiors and exteriors buildings, structures and ground surfaces where a more specific code from 4241 through 4249 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Paneling and trim
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of paneling and trim materials, typically made of wood, fiberboard, or PVC.
metadata.includes: Beadboard; wooden shingles; decorative millwork, baseboards, moldings
metadata.excludes: Pallets of materials (217); bundles of materials (2141); walls- structurally attached (655)

metadata.title: Bricks and pavers— stone and masonry
metadata.definition: Unattached bricks and stone surfacing materials.
metadata.includes: Building and landscaping bricks; outdoor pavers; stone and brick façade; decorative stone; fire bricks
metadata.excludes: Cinder blocks, structural blocks (4212); Pallets of materials (217); finished ground surfaces (662)

metadata.title: Exterior siding
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of exterior siding, typically used to protect the frame of a house from weather conditions.
metadata.includes: Aluminum, vinyl, wood or composite siding; cedar shakes, shingles

metadata.title: Interior flooring
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of flooring, either in larger sections or modular sheets or panels.
metadata.includes: Sheets or tiles made of vinyl, linoleum, or asbestos used as floor coverings

metadata.title: Tiles— ceramic, stone, glass
metadata.definition: Unattached tiles made from a range of materials and used for a variety of purposes.
metadata.includes: Decorative tiles; mosaic tiles; roof tiles; floor tiles; shower tiles; fireproof tiles

metadata.title: Roofing shingles and sheets
metadata.definition: Unattached roofing materials.
metadata.includes: Roof flashing; asphalt shingles; Solar roof shingles (TeslaTM)
metadata.excludes: Solar panels (4514); bundles of shingles (214); house siding shingles (4243); roofing asphalt, tar (4161); roofing paper (4251)

metadata.title: Drop ceiling tiles
metadata.definition: Unattached sections of paneling and trim materials.

metadata.title: Multiple finishing and surfacing materials
metadata.definition: Unattached materials that are used for surfacing and finishing the interiors and exteriors buildings, structures and ground surfaces where more than one type of material from codes 4241 through 4249 are involved.
metadata.excludes: Pallets of materials (217); bundles of materials (2141)

metadata.title: Finishing and surfacing materials— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Unattached materials that are used for surfacing and finishing the interiors and exteriors buildings, structures and ground surfaces where the specified material does not match descriptions of codes 4241 through 4248.

metadata.title: Flexible barriers, coverings
metadata.definition: This source group consists of individual, unattached materials are used as flexible barriers (either air and water-tight or porous). Codes from this group do not pertain to quantities of building materials grouped into containers, packages, or bundles. They must also be unattached to or separated from a structure.
metadata.includes: Insulation; fencing; screening
metadata.excludes: Paints, caulking and adhesives (43); rolls or bundles of material (214)

metadata.title: Flexible barriers, coverings— unspecified
metadata.definition: Unattached materials are used as flexible barriers where a more specific code from 4251 through 4259 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Tarps, liners, wraps
metadata.definition: Flexible coverings and barriers, often used as a permanent sub layer of air and moisture protection below the outermost surface of buildings and structures or as a removable protective cover for surfaces, structures or other items.
metadata.includes: House wrap paper, vinyl and PVC liners; roof paper and felt

metadata.title: Insulation— fiberglass
metadata.definition: Flexible panels of spun glass fibers used as a thermal insulator in buildings.
metadata.excludes: Rolls or bundles of material (214); foam insulation (431)

metadata.title: Fencing and screening material
metadata.definition: Lengths of sheeting consisting of wires or other materials woven in an open pattern consisting of variously sized holes, depending on its intended use.
metadata.includes: Chain link and wire fencing; hardware cloth; screening; silt fence
metadata.excludes: Rolls of fencing and screening (2143); fences (6334); gates (6335); prefabricated wood and PVC fencing panels (4239)

metadata.title: Multiple flexible barriers, coverings
metadata.definition: Unattached materials are used as flexible barriers where more than one type of material from codes 4251 through 4259 are involved.

metadata.title: Flexible barriers, coverings— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Unattached materials are used as flexible barriers where the specified material does not match descriptions of codes 4251 through 4258.
metadata.includes: Blow in (cellulose) insulation; rock wool, mineral wool; carbon fiber applications; steel wool
metadata.excludes: Paints, caulking and adhesives, foam insulation (43)

metadata.title: Concrete— wet mix, or dry mix
metadata.definition: Dry concrete mix or wet concrete that is flowable and not yet hardened into its final form.
metadata.includes: Mortar; cement
metadata.excludes: Buildings (62); Structures (63); concrete building materials (42); finished ground surfaces (662)

metadata.title: Multiple building materials
metadata.definition: Building materials where more than one type of material from code groups 421 through 429 are involved.
metadata.includes: Lumber and panels; drywall and insulation

metadata.title: Building materials n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Building materials where the specified material does not match descriptions in code groups 421 through 428.
metadata.includes: Dowel rods; shims; wooden stakes

metadata.title: Adhesives, sealants, paints
metadata.definition: This major group classifies materials that are applied as a liquid which are primarily used to seal gaps or openings in structures, glue objects together, or provide a protective and/or decorative finish when dried.
metadata.excludes: Tar or asphalt (4161); bottles, cans or containers of paints, adhesives, etc. (21)

metadata.title: Adhesives, sealants, paints— unspecified
metadata.definition: Materials that are applied as a liquid which are primarily used as sealants, glues or protective and/or decorative finishes when dried where a more specific code from 431 through 439 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Caulking, insulation— foam
metadata.definition: Material that expands to a foam when applied to fill in gaps in structures.

metadata.title: Caulking— plastic, vinyl
metadata.definition: Material made of liquid plastic or vinyl that is applied to fill gaps in structures.
metadata.includes: Plumbing caulk

metadata.title: Glues, adhesives
metadata.definition: Substances used to stick materials together.
metadata.includes: Epoxies; resins; glues

metadata.title: Paint, lacquer, shellac, varnish
metadata.definition: Liquid substances applied to provide protective and decorative finishes on surfaces once dry.
metadata.includes: Latex and oil based paints; polyurethane; shellac; varnish; stains

metadata.title: Multiple adhesives, sealants, and paints
metadata.definition: Materials that are applied as a liquid which are primarily used as sealants, glues or protective and/or decorative finishes where more than one type of material from codes 431 through 439 are involved.
metadata.includes: Tape and glue

metadata.title: Adhesives, sealants, and paints— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Materials that are applied as a liquid which are primarily used as sealants, glues or protective and/or decorative finishes where the specified material does not match descriptions of codes 431 through 438.
metadata.includes: Joint compound; patching compound; pipe dope

metadata.title: Fasteners, connectors, ropes, ties
metadata.definition: This major group classifies fasteners, connectors, and binders that are primarily used to hold materials together. Codes from this group do not pertain to quantities of materials grouped into containers, packages, or bundles. They must also be unattached to or separated from the object(s) they are securing.

metadata.title: Fasteners, connectors, ropes, ties— unspecified
metadata.definition: Fasteners, connectors, and binders where a more specific code from 4410 through 449 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Fasteners
metadata.definition: This source group classifies any of various devices that are used to attach, connect, or secure things together. Codes from this group do not pertain to quantities of materials grouped into containers, packages, or bundles. They must also be unattached to or separated from the object(s) they are securing.

metadata.title: Fasteners— unspecified
metadata.definition: Devices that are used to attach, connect, or secure things together where a more specific code from 4411 through 4419 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Clamps, couplings
metadata.definition: Devices for connecting and pressing together machine or other parts.

metadata.title: Nails, brads, tacks, spikes
metadata.definition: Small metal spikes typically driven into wood or other softer materials to join them together.
metadata.includes: Carpet tack strips

metadata.title: Door and window hardware— Hinges, latches, etc.
metadata.definition: Hardware used to allow doors to open, close and swing freely within its frame.
metadata.includes: Knobs, latches, locks, hinges

metadata.title: Rivets, bolts
metadata.definition: Metal pins or bolts for holding sheets of metal together.

metadata.title: Screws
metadata.definition: Metal pins with a raised helical thread running around it and a slotted head, used to join things together by being rotated so that it pierces wood or other material and is held tightly in place.
metadata.includes: Wafer head screw; wood screw; machine screw

metadata.title: Pipe fittings, collars
metadata.definition: Fittings or adapters used in systems of pipes to connect sections of pipe, adapt to different sizes or shapes, and for other purposes such as regulating fluid flow.
metadata.includes: Flange; coupling; adapter; elbow

metadata.title: Staples
metadata.definition: Bits of bent wire with two bent points used to fasten objects together.
metadata.includes: Paper staples; wood staples

metadata.title: Multiple fasteners
metadata.definition: Devices that are used to attach, connect, or secure things together where more than one type of material from codes 4411 through 4419 are involved.

metadata.title: Fasteners— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Devices that are used to attach, connect, or secure things together where the specified material does not match descriptions of codes 4411 through 4418.
metadata.includes: Nuts, washers

metadata.title: Ropes, ties, chains
metadata.definition: This source group classifies ropes and ties of any composition that are used primarily for pulling, securing or binding things together. Codes from this group do not pertain to quantities of materials grouped into containers, packages, or bundles. They must also be unattached to or separated from the object(s) they are securing.

metadata.title: Ropes, ties, chains— unspecified
metadata.definition: Ropes and ties where a more specific code from 4421 through 4429 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Bungee cords
metadata.definition: Large, elastic bands used to secure items.

metadata.title: Chains
metadata.definition: A connected flexible series of metal links used for fastening or securing objects and pulling or supporting loads.

metadata.title: Rope, twine, string
metadata.definition: Lengths of cord made by twisting together strands of natural  or artificial fibers used to fasten, secure, or pull objects.
metadata.includes: Mooring line; boat line

metadata.title: Strapping, bands
metadata.definition: Lengths of flexible material (often woven) used for fasten and securing objects.
metadata.includes: Ratchet straps

metadata.title: Wire, cables—nonelectrified
metadata.definition: Lengths of flexible wire used to pull and secure objects as well as wire intended for electrical purposes that is not attached to a building or machine.
metadata.includes: Guy wires (unattached); detached electrical wiring; barbed and razor wire (except for part of fence structure)

metadata.title: Multiple ropes, ties, chains— unspecified
metadata.definition: Ropes and ties where more than one type of material from codes 4421 through 4429 are involved.

metadata.title: Ropes, ties, chains— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Ropes and ties where the specified material does not match descriptions of codes 4420 through 4428.
metadata.includes: Cargo net, webbing, zip ties

metadata.title: Valves, nozzles
metadata.definition: Valves are devices for controlling the passage of fluid or air through a pipe, duct, etc., especially an automatic device allowing movement in one direction only. Nozzles are spouts at the end of a hose used to control streams of gas or liquids.
metadata.excludes: Pipe fittings (4416); oil and gas wellhead valves (3254)

metadata.title: Multiple fasteners, connectors, ropes, ties
metadata.definition: Fasteners, connectors, and binders where more than one type of material from descriptions of codes in groups 441 through 449 are involved.

metadata.title: Fasteners, connectors, ropes, ties— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Fasteners, connectors, and binders where the specified material does not match descriptions of code groups 441 through 448.

metadata.title: Hoisting accessories
metadata.definition: This major group classifies unattached hoisting accessories which are primarily used in conjunction with the hoisting machinery classified in source group 343 (Overhead hoists). These are primarily hoisting machinery attachments designed to grip, pick up, or carry heavy materials.
metadata.excludes: Cranes, derricks (342); hoisting machinery (343); oil and gas extraction machinery (325)

metadata.title: Hoisting accessories— unspecified
metadata.definition: Unattached hoisting accessories where a more specific code from 451 through 459 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Fixtures, load indicators
metadata.definition: Several types of lifting accessories, including devices which alert the operator if the lift is exceeding the safe operating range of the machinery.

metadata.title: Hooks, shackles, magnets, clamshells
metadata.definition: Equipment typically used with hoisting and winching machinery that attach to or hold onto materials being lifted or moved.

metadata.title: Slings
metadata.definition: Flexible straps or belts used in the form of a loop to support or raise a weight.
metadata.includes: Chain sling; web sling

metadata.title: Drums, pulleys, sheaves
metadata.definition: A configuration of grooved wheels in conjunction with belts, cables, or ropes where the wheel spins on an axle and allows the wire or rope to move freely in order to minimize friction and wear on the cable.
metadata.includes: Block and tackle; traveling block; crown block; winches and accompanying cable
metadata.excludes: Cranes, derricks (342); hoisting machinery (343); oil and gas extraction machinery (325)

metadata.title: Multiple hoisting accessories
metadata.definition: Unattached hoisting accessories where more than one type of material from codes 451 through 459 are involved.

metadata.title: Hoisting accessories— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Unattached hoisting accessories where the specified material does not match descriptions of codes 451 through 458.

metadata.title: Vehicle and machine parts— power, mechanical, special process
metadata.definition: This major group classifies unattached machine, tool, electric, and vehicle parts and materials.
metadata.excludes: Vehicle parts (47); whole machines (Division 3); whole tools (Division 7)

metadata.title: Vehicle and machine parts— unspecified
metadata.definition: Unattached machine, tool, electric, and vehicle parts and materials where a more specific code from 4610 through 469 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Electric parts
metadata.definition: This source group classifies electric parts which primarily generate or carry electrical currents for machinery, vehicles, and other sources which require electrical systems. All codes below include associated wiring and other incidental components.
metadata.includes: Installed and uninstalled components of electrical systems; Components of electrical systems that are not energized
metadata.excludes: Vehicle parts (47); whole machines (Division 3); whole tools (Division 7); computer parts (except power cords) (466)

metadata.title: Electric parts— unspecified
metadata.definition: Electric parts where a more specific code from 4611 through 4619 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Electrical wiring—building or machine
metadata.definition: System of wiring that is attached to buildings, structures, vehicles or machinery in order to provide power.
metadata.includes: Wires; outlets; light switches
metadata.excludes: Building electric panels, fuse boxes (4615); whole buildings, structures (Division 6); air conditioning and heating equipment (331); unattached pipes, ducts (422); unattached electrical wire (4425)

metadata.title: Power lines, transformers, convertors
metadata.definition: Systems of electrical cables and related parts used to distribute electric power over long distances.
metadata.includes: Overhead power lines; underground power lines

metadata.title: Power cords, electrical cords, extension cords
metadata.definition: Electrical cables that temporarily connect machines and appliances to an electricity supply via a socket.
metadata.includes: Computer cables; extension cords; power strips

metadata.title: Solar panels
metadata.definition: Devices that convert solar energy to electrical energy.

metadata.title: Switchboards, panels, fuses
metadata.definition: Devices that direct electricity from one or more sources of supply to several smaller regions of usage as well as fuses, which stop or interrupt the current when necessary.
metadata.includes: Building electric panels, fuse boxes, switches, electric cabinets

metadata.title: Multiple electric parts
metadata.definition: Electric parts where more than one component from codes 4611 through 4619 are involved.
metadata.includes: Building wiring and fuse box

metadata.title: Electric parts— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Electric parts where the specified component does not match descriptions of codes 4610 through 4618.
metadata.includes: Relays, rheostats, starters, controls, conductors

metadata.title: Engine, motor, and mechanical parts
metadata.definition: This source group classifies equipment designed to convert combustion heat or other kinds of energy into mechanical force. Engines and motors may be powered by any type of fuel, electricity, or some combination (hybrid vehicles).
metadata.includes: Combustion engine; electric motors; hybrid engines

metadata.title: Engine, motor, and mechanical parts— unspecified
metadata.definition: Equipment designed to convert combustion heat or other kinds of energy into mechanical force where specific code from 4621 through 4629 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Combustion engine blocks, cylinders, pistons
metadata.definition: Cylinder block or casings for cylinders and pistons used for combustion.
metadata.includes: Cylinder block

metadata.title: Drives, belts, chains
metadata.definition: Belts or chains that transmit drive from a motor, engine, or line shaft to a moving part or machine tool.
metadata.includes: Chain, leather, fabric, vee belt, serpentine belt; timing belt; V-belt

metadata.title: Springs, coils
metadata.definition: Devices which are typically used to store energy and subsequently release it, to absorb shock, or to maintain a force between contacting surfaces. They are made of an elastic material formed into the shape of a helix.
metadata.includes: Compression springs; extension springs; torsion springs; garter spring

metadata.title: Fan and turbine parts
metadata.definition: Wheels or rotors with attached blades used to create a currents of air or fluid for cooling, ventilation, or propulsion or to convert currents of air or fluid into rotational energy.
metadata.includes: Rotors, blades, shafts
metadata.excludes: Wind energy turbines (6354); stand-alone fans or ventilation machines (3312)

metadata.title: Radiators
metadata.definition: Heat exchangers used for cooling internal combustion engines by circulation of cooling fluid through the engine and allowing it to re-cool in the radiator.

metadata.title: Transmissions, gears
metadata.definition: Machine devices that adapt the energy output by the vehicle or machine engine to the drive wheels or other mechanical parts. The transmission reduces the higher engine speed to the slower wheel speed, increasing torque in the process to aid in starting, stopping and slower travel.
metadata.includes: Gears; shafts; shifting components; clutch

metadata.title: Multiple engine and mechanical parts, whole engine
metadata.definition: Engine and motor parts and mechanical components where more than one part from codes 4621 through 4628 are involved.
metadata.includes: Whole engine

metadata.title: Engine, motor, and mechanical parts— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Equipment designed to convert combustion heat or other kinds of energy into mechanical force where the specified component does not match descriptions of codes 4620 through 4628.
metadata.includes: Alternator; vehicle computer

metadata.title: Machine hydraulics and pressurized components
metadata.definition: This source group classifies machine hydraulics and pressurized components.

metadata.title: Machine hydraulics and pressurized components— unspecified
metadata.definition: Vehicle or machinery hydraulic and pressurized components where a specific code from 4631 through 4639 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Hydraulic and pressurized cylinders
metadata.definition: Vehicle or machinery components consisting of pressurized cylinders or cylinders that function as part of a hydraulic system.

metadata.title: Hydraulic and pressurized hoses, lines
metadata.definition: Vehicle or machinery components consisting of flexible lines or tubes that contain or conduct pressurized substances or are part of a hydraulic system.
metadata.includes: Hydraulic, pneumatic, engine and motor, pressure lines

metadata.title: Pressurized pipes— vehicle and machine
metadata.definition: Vehicle or machinery components consisting of rigid pipes or tubes that contain or conduct pressurized substances.
metadata.excludes: building plumbing (642); sewer and pipeline interiors (6122, 6123); pressurized containers (212); unattached ducts, tubes, pipes (422)

metadata.title: Multiple machine hydraulics and pressurized components
metadata.definition: Vehicle or machinery hydraulic and pressurized components where more than one part from codes 4631 through 4633 are involved.

metadata.title: Machine hydraulics and pressurized components— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Vehicle or machinery hydraulic and pressurized components where the specified component does not match descriptions of codes 4630 through 4638.

metadata.title: Machine and tool parts, accessories— special process
metadata.definition: This source group classifies tool parts and accessories.

metadata.title: Machine and tool parts, accessories— unspecified
metadata.definition: Tool parts and accessories where a more specific code from 4641 through 4649 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: "Part of machine detached" without further description

metadata.title: Drill bits
metadata.definition: Metal pins of various thicknesses with a helical groove, used to bore holes with the use of a drill.
metadata.includes: Wood bits; masonry bits; flat bits

metadata.title: Saw blades
metadata.definition: Discs or bands with grooved teeth for cutting materials with use of a saw.
metadata.includes: Circular saw blade; band saw blade

metadata.title: Dies, molds, patterns
metadata.definition: Forms or templates used to shape or cut intermediate materials for production.

metadata.title: Rollers, cylinders
metadata.definition: Cylinders that rotate around a central axis, which are used to move, flatten, or spread something.
metadata.excludes: Tires, inner tubes, wheel rims (471); calendering machines (Division 3)

metadata.title: Multiple tool parts, accessories
metadata.definition: Tool parts and accessories where more than one type of material from codes 4641 through 4649 are involved.
metadata.includes: Safety guard and blade

metadata.title: Machine and tool parts, accessories— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Tool parts and accessories where the specified material does not match descriptions of codes 4641 through 4648.
metadata.includes: Filters; finger guard; knobs; handles; grinder head

metadata.title: Batteries and related equipment
metadata.definition: This source group includes devices that are capable of storing electrical energy, or containing chemical energy, which can be converted into electricity and used as a source of power  where a more specific code from 4651 through 4659 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Batteries and related equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Devices that are capable of storing electrical energy, or containing chemical energy, which can be converted into electricity and used as a source of power

metadata.title: Batteries
metadata.definition: Devices that are capable of storing electrical energy, or containing chemical energy, which can be converted into electricity and used as a source of power.
metadata.includes: AA; AAA; D; 9-volt; button cell; computer batteries; Lithium ion; Lead acid; rechargeable; vanadium flow; industrial batteries; battery charging equipment; vehicle battery

metadata.title: Battery charging equipment
metadata.definition: Equipment used to recharge batteries with electricity.
metadata.includes: Electric vehicle charging stations; cell phone chargers

metadata.title: Batteries related equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Battery-related equipment that does not match codes 4651 through 4652.

metadata.title: Computer parts, components
metadata.definition: Parts and components that are specific to computers or computerized components or control panels of larger vehicles and machinery.

metadata.title: Bodily conditions of injured, ill worker
metadata.definition: This source group classifies physical, or mental conditions of the injured or ill worker that actively caused or contributed to a harmful workplace event or exposure. These are typically pre-existing conditions. Do not select a code from 561 if the worker's bodily condition exacerbated the nature of the workplace injury but did not contribute to the event that caused it. For example, a worker strikes his leg against a table and suffers prolonged bleeding because of his underlying bleeding condition. Here the bleeding condition did not cause the worker to strike his leg. However, the nature of his injury was more severe because of his condition.
metadata.includes: Worker suffers syncope and falls, bumping head; worker suffer heart attack and crashes vehicle

metadata.title: Bodily conditions of injured, ill worker— unspecified
metadata.definition: Bodily conditions of injured or ill worker, where a more specific code from 5611 to 5619 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: "Stress" ; fainting without indication of other condition

metadata.title: Mental illness, impairment of injured, ill worker
metadata.definition: Underlying conditions affecting mental soundness and stability.
metadata.includes: PTSD, depression, dementia; Alzheimer's; and any other listed in the DSM-5 from the American Psychiatric Association.; "mental break", "psychotic break"

metadata.title: Cardiovascular, respiratory conditions of injured, ill worker
metadata.definition: Underlying conditions of the heart, lungs, and vascular systems.
metadata.includes: Stroke, heart attack; effects of COPD and allied conditions

metadata.title: Neurological conditions of injured, ill worker
metadata.definition: Underlying conditions of the neurological system.
metadata.includes: Epileptic seizure; syncope, "black out", fainting

metadata.title: Asthma, allergies of injured, ill worker
metadata.definition: Underlying conditions of asthma or allergies
metadata.includes: Asthma attack due to allergic reaction; Hay fever; allergic reaction

metadata.title: Musculoskeletal conditions of injured, ill worker
metadata.definition: Underlying conditions of the bones, muscles and connective tissues.
metadata.includes: Arthritis

metadata.title: Bodily conditions of injured, ill worker— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Bodily conditions of injured, ill worker that does not match descriptions of codes 5611 through 5615.
metadata.includes: Side effects of prescribed medications (e.g. drowsiness from antihistamine use causes roadway collision); conditions related to pregnancy; diabetes; illnesses not related to work; pre-exiting skin conditions e.g. eczema, psoriasis

metadata.title: Bodily motion or position of injured, ill worker
metadata.definition: This code describes stress or strains induced by a free movement of the body or its parts, with no impact involved. It is also used for coding awkward or sustained positions of the injured worker as well as the motion of the person for motion sickness cases.

metadata.title: Activities and conditions of injured, ill worker— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: This code is used as the source for suicides and other intentional self-inflicted injuries.
metadata.includes: suicides, punching wall

metadata.title: Person—other than injured or ill worker
metadata.definition: This major group classifies various types of persons other than the injured or ill worker. In general, people are classified according to their relationship with the injured or ill worker or with the establishment for which the employee works.  If a person can be classified in more than one category (5710-579), choose the first code in the list describing the person’s relationship with the injured worker or establishment. For example, if a co-worker robs a business, choose co-worker (5721) because it is listed before robber. However, if a police officer is shot while trying to apprehend a person who had robbed a store, use code 5762, Suspect under pursuit or investigation, since the robber was not trying to rob the police officer.

metadata.title: Person, other than injured or ill worker— unspecified
metadata.definition: Person, other than injured or ill worker, where a more specific code from 5710 to 579 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Relative or domestic partner of injured or ill worker
metadata.definition: This source group classifies those with a familial relationship to the injured or ill worker.

metadata.title: Relative or domestic partner of injured or ill worker— unspecified
metadata.definition: This source group classifies those with a familial relationship to the injured or ill worker when a more specific code from 5711 through 5719 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Spouse or domestic partner of injured or ill worker
metadata.definition: Persons who were involved in a current romantic relationship with the injured or ill worker at the time of injury.
metadata.includes: Spouse (husband, wife, common law spouse); civil union; other domestic partner (boyfriend, girlfriend)
metadata.excludes: Other room- or house-mates (575); relative other than spouse (5713 or 5719)

metadata.title: Former or estranged partner of injured or ill worker
metadata.definition: Persons who were previously involved in a romantic relationship with the injured or ill worker where the relationship had been terminated before the time of injury.
metadata.includes: Divorced, separated, ex-spouse, estranged spouse, ex-husband, ex-wife, ex-boyfriend, ex-girlfriend, estranged boyfriend or girlfriend

metadata.title: Immediate family member other than partner
metadata.definition: Persons with immediate family ties to the injured or ill worker, either biologically or through marriage or adoption.
metadata.includes: Children or offspring (son, daughter, step-children); parent (father, mother, step-parent); sibling (brother, sister, step-siblings)

metadata.title: Other relative of injured or ill worker— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Persons with family ties to the injured or ill worker who are not an immediate family member.
metadata.includes: Uncle, aunt, cousin, nephew, niece, grandson, granddaughter, in-laws, grandparent

metadata.title: Co-worker or work associate of injured or ill worker
metadata.definition: This source group classifies those with a professional relationship to the injured or ill worker.
metadata.includes: Employee or past employee of the business; on-site and off-site contractors; temporary employees

metadata.title: Co-worker or work associate of injured or ill worker— unspecified
metadata.definition: This source group classifies those with a professional relationship to the injured or ill worker when a more specific code from 5721 through 5729 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Co-worker, supervisor— current
metadata.definition: Co-workers and supervisors are defined as persons who worked for the same employer and regularly interacted on the same or related work at the time of injury. Co-workers are typically peers, while supervisors are responsible for overseeing the injured workers work stream in some capacity. For example, for a nurse working in a hospital, doctors, nurses, supervisory nurses, technicians, and others who work directly with that nurse are co-workers.
metadata.includes: Long term, on-site contracted workers working with regular employees; boss, supervisor, team lead; coworkers who normally work remotely; athletic team member or fellow trainee

metadata.title: Co-worker, supervisor— former
metadata.definition: Co-workers and supervisors are defined as persons who had previously worked for the same employer and regularly interacted on the same or related work before the occurrence of the injury. Co-workers are typically peers, while supervisors are responsible for overseeing the injured workers work stream in some capacity.
metadata.includes: recently fired or laid off employees; Supervisors or co-workers at jobs which the injured worker recently left

metadata.title: Work associate— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Work associates are individuals when work (or have previously worked) for the same establishment or in the same building, but do not have regular work interactions.  For example, for a nurse working in a hospital, other, non-clinical employees of the hospital, such as security, food service, or administrative personnel, would likely be work associates. These may also be persons that had regular or semi-regular work interactions but do not work for the same company or establishment. For example, a restaurant owner who buys produce from a local farmer. This source code also classifies those with a professional relationship to the injured or ill worker when details are known but do not match descriptions of codes 5721 through 5722.
metadata.includes: Business competitors; business suppliers; Former work associate; business contacts; off-site contracted workers; Athletic and sports opponents

metadata.title: Student, patient, charge
metadata.definition: This source group classifies persons for whom the injured worker's relationship is that of a personal care provider or of custodial oversight in nature.

metadata.title: Student, patient, charge— unspecified
metadata.definition: This source group classifies relationships of a personal care provider or of custodial oversight in nature when a more specific code from 5731 through 5739 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Student
metadata.definition: Persons for whom the injured or ill worker bears authority and responsibility for their education and well-being.
metadata.includes: Students in primary or secondary school; college, university students; preschool students
metadata.excludes: Student inmates (5761); students or clients in other types of training programs, such as martial arts or flight training (574)

metadata.title: Patient
metadata.definition: Persons under the medical care of the injured or ill worker.
metadata.includes: Patients receiving care at any type of healthcare facility (doctor’s and dentist’s offices, hospitals, nursing homes, and mental health facilities);  patients cared for in their own homes; patients of emergency medical services
metadata.excludes: Mental health patients who have committed a crime and are in a correctional facility (5761); residents of halfway houses and assisted living facilities (5733)

metadata.title: Other charge or ward
metadata.definition: Any other type of person for whom the worker bears formal responsibility for the oversight of that person's well-being, education, or safety.
metadata.includes: Social services clients and wards; children in non-school daycare or private childcare; resident of halfway house or assisted living facility not receiving medical care
metadata.excludes: Resident of halfway house or assisted living facility receiving medical care from the injured or ill worker (5732)

metadata.title: Family member or associate of student, patient or charge
metadata.definition: Family members or other persons who interact with the injured worker on behalf of or in support of a student, patient or charge.
metadata.includes: Family member of patient; friend of patient

metadata.title: Client or customer
metadata.definition: This code includes persons with a legitimate relationship with the business and who are being served by the business.
metadata.includes: Bar patron, tenant,  students or trainees of activities where the instructor is not an authority figure (i.e. fitness trainees, private music lesson clients)
metadata.excludes: Health care patients (5732), inmates of correctional facilities (5761), robbers posing as customers (5763)

metadata.title: Acquaintance
metadata.definition: This code includes all other persons known to the injured worker or his or her coworkers.
metadata.includes: Friend, neighbor, roommate other than domestic partner, member of same gang; family member or friend of coworker
metadata.excludes: Family member (571*), client (574), boyfriend or girlfriend (5711), patient (5732), co-worker (572*)

metadata.title: Criminal assailants
metadata.definition: This group includes assailants who's relationship with the injured worker is defined by assailant's previous criminal activity in the absence of another type of personal or professional relationship listed above.   Although assault or other acts of violence are criminal, code 570 should be selected if the relationship between the decedent and assailant is not known.
metadata.includes: robbers; persons either convicted or suspected of a crime who are interacting with law enforcement and justice workers
metadata.excludes: 5700 should be selected if the relationship between the decedent and assailant is not known

metadata.title: Criminal assailant— unspecified
metadata.definition: This group includes assailants who's relationship with the injured worker is defined by assailant's previous criminal activity when a more specific code from 5761 to 5769 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Criminal inmate or detainee in custody
metadata.definition: These are incarcerated assailants and other persons under various degrees of law enforcement custody or supervision.
metadata.includes: Parolees; prison inmates, student inmates, jail inmates; people under arrest; other detainees
metadata.excludes: Patients in sanitariums and mental facilities (5732)

metadata.title: Suspect under pursuit or investigation
metadata.definition: This group is for criminal assailants who kill/assault a worker who is interacting with them in a public safety capacity, either pursuit or investigation. This code will generally apply to public safety workers while they are discharging their duties.
metadata.includes: Criminals who shoot a police officer while being approached, questioned, apprehended, or fleeing; this also includes traffic stops or other public safety related incidents that turn violent

metadata.title: Robber
metadata.definition: Assailants who act violently for the primary purpose of stealing.

metadata.title: Criminal assailant— except robber
metadata.definition: These are criminal assailants who kill/assault a worker where the motive is known and is not robbery.
metadata.includes: Shooting sprees, murder for hire, hate crimes, sexual assaults, gang initiations, kidnapping; this includes unintended victims like those injured in a shooting spree who were not the intended targets

metadata.title: Person, other than injured or ill worker— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Persons, other than injured, ill worker that does not match descriptions in codes 5710 through 5769.
metadata.includes: Police intervention in public safety situation; public safety workers who shoot a worker

metadata.title: Persons, plants, animals, and minerals— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: This code classifies plants, animals, and other organic materials not elsewhere classified in Division 5.

metadata.title: STRUCTURES AND SURFACES
metadata.definition: Codes in this division classify all types of structures and structural elements including building structures and systems, bridges, stadia, tunnels, towers, and dams as well as confined spaces, structural elements and surfaces, and natural structures.
metadata.includes: building systems; floors, ramps and walkways, ground surfaces; structural elements such as doors, windows, roof, decks; structures; fixed ladders
metadata.excludes: bricks, blocks, structural stone (4242); unattached structural metals (42); unattached building materials (42); moveable ladders (73)

metadata.title: Structures and surfaces— unspecified
metadata.definition: Structure or structural element with too little information to choose a code from 610 through 69.

metadata.title: Confined spaces
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify structures that are considered confined because their configurations hinder the activities of employees while occupying them. A confined space has limited or restricted means for entry or exit, is not designed for continuous employee occupancy, and poses an increased risk of exposure to serious physical injury from hazards such as entrapment, engulfment and hazardous atmospheric conditions. A workspace is included if it contains, or has the potential to contain a hazardous atmosphere; contains a material that has the potential to engulf an entrant; or has walls that converge inward or floors that slope downward and taper in a smaller area which could trap or asphyxiate an entrant. Spaces coded in this section may include spaces not considered as confined according to OSHA. These codes would typically be used as the secondary source for incidents involving confined spaces.
metadata.includes: confined ditches, channels, trenches; underground vaults, tanks, storage bins; manholes; pits; silos; process vessels; pipelines; underground mines and tunnels; tanker truck interiors; confined spaces on ships and other vehicles
metadata.excludes: buildings (62), passenger vehicles (84); nonconfined ditches or trenches (6)

metadata.title: Confined spaces— unspecified
metadata.definition: Spaces that are known to be confined but do not have enough information to choose a code from 611 to 6149.

metadata.title: Ditches, channels, trenches, excavations
metadata.definition: Ground spaces that are open vertically but confined on the sides.
metadata.includes: ditches, channels, trenches, excavation pits
metadata.excludes: vertically confined spaces such as mines, caves, tunnels or pipes (612); non-confined culverts and ditches (6633)

metadata.title: Mines, caves, tunnels, pipes
metadata.definition: Spaces that are vertically confined but open on the sides or ends.
metadata.includes: underground mines, caves; sewers and storm drains; manholes; culverts; tunnels (including subway, train, sewer, and pedestrian tunnels)
metadata.excludes: ditches, channels, trenches, excavations (611); bridges (632); above-ground mines, strip mines (637); non-confined culverts or ditches (6633)

metadata.title: Mines, caves, tunnels, pipes— unspecified
metadata.definition: Vertically confined spaces with too little information to choose a code from 6121 through 6129.
metadata.includes: pipelines of unknown type

metadata.title: Underground mines, mine tunnels
metadata.definition: Interior of underground mines and access ways.

metadata.title: Sewers, drains, water pipes
metadata.definition: Interior of sewers and storm drains and access ways to these structures.
metadata.includes: water mains, sewers, manholes, storm drains; gas and oil pipelines; culverts

metadata.title: Oil and gas pipeline
metadata.definition: Interiors of oil and gas transport pipelines.

metadata.title: Pedestrian, subway, train tunnels
metadata.definition: Interior of tunnels used for train, subway or pedestrian travel.
metadata.includes: passageway, train shaft

metadata.title: Mines, caves, tunnels, pipes— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Vertically confined spaces that are known but do not match codes 6121 through 6124.

metadata.title: Tank, bin, vat interiors
metadata.definition: The interior of a large receptacle or storage chamber with only one method of entrance or exit.
metadata.includes: tank interiors on vehicles
metadata.excludes: entire tank, bin, vat or dumpster (2115)

metadata.title: Tank, bin, vat interiors— unspecified
metadata.definition: The interior of a large receptacle or storage chamber with too little information to choose a code from 6131 through 6139.
metadata.includes: storage vat interior

metadata.title: Silo, grain bin or elevator interiors
metadata.definition: Interior of a receptacle used for bulk storage of grain, food products, coal, cement, woodchips, sawdust, etc.
metadata.includes: granary, grain crib interiors

metadata.title: Hopper interior
metadata.definition: Interior of a hopper.
metadata.includes: hoppers on vehicles

metadata.title: Septic or water tank interiors
metadata.definition: Interior of receptacles used for storage of sewage or water.
metadata.includes: water tower, cesspit or cesspool interior; vehicle water tank interior

metadata.title: Trash bin or dumpster interiors
metadata.definition: Interior of a receptacle used for storage of trash or refuse.

metadata.title: Oil and gas tank interiors
metadata.definition: Interior of a tank used for storage of gas or oil.
metadata.includes: Vehicle oil tank interior

metadata.title: Tank, bin, vat interiors— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: The interior of a large receptacle or storage chamber that is known but does not match codes from 6131 through 6135.
metadata.excludes: exterior or entire receptacle or storage chamber (21)

metadata.title: Other confined spaces
metadata.definition: Confined spaces not listed in codes 611 through 613.

metadata.title: Crawl spaces
metadata.definition: A hollow area in a building beneath the first floor or under the roof usually used for access to plumbing, heating or cooling and electrical systems, just high enough for a person to access the space by crawling.
metadata.includes: attic

metadata.title: Wells, cisterns
metadata.definition: Interior of in ground receptacles used for water storage. It can be used for collection of rainwater or access to underground water sources.
metadata.includes: well, cistern

metadata.title: Manure pits, ponds
metadata.definition: Ground storage of animal manure in an excavated hole. It can be open to the environment or covered.
metadata.includes: manure pit or pond
metadata.excludes: interior of manure vats or tanks (613)

metadata.title: Spray, paint booths
metadata.definition: Enclosed chamber used for applying paint and other coatings and finishes in a controlled environment.
metadata.includes: spraying chamber, paint booth

metadata.title: Elevator shafts
metadata.definition: A vertical passageway in a structure to permit movement of an elevator.

metadata.title: Vehicle confined spaces— except tanks, bins, vats
metadata.definition: Confined spaces on land, air or water vehicles, except those listed in group 613.
metadata.includes: ship holds, aircraft cargo areas, bilge

metadata.title: Other confined spaces— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Confined spaces that are known but do not match codes 611 through 6146.

metadata.title: Buildings
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify all types and sizes of buildings including office, plant, commercial, institutional and residential buildings. Buildings are structures with roofs, walls and floors that are intended for permanent use.
metadata.includes: homes, apartment buildings, government and office buildings, warehouses, retail stores, plants, factories, condominiums, schools, hospitals, medical offices, prisons, courthouses, airport buildings, garage
metadata.excludes: interiors of structures that are defined as confined spaces (61); floors, stairs, escalators, fixed ladders of buildings (66); structural elements of buildings such as windows (652) or doors (651)

metadata.title: Building— unspecified
metadata.definition: Building of unknown type with too little information to choose a code from 621 through 629.

metadata.title: Industrial building
metadata.definition: Permanent, industrial buildings of any height.
metadata.includes: factory, plant, shop, industrial parking garage, utility building

metadata.title: Commercial or institutional building
metadata.definition: Permanent, commercial or institutional building of any height.
metadata.includes: school, hospital, prison, office building, store, mall, airport, commercial or institutional parking garage; open or closed arenas; grandstands; stadiums

metadata.title: Residential building
metadata.definition: Permanent, residential building of any height.
metadata.includes: apartment building, ranch house, condo, dorm, residential parking garage

metadata.title: Silos
metadata.definition: Cylindrical building or tower made of any material that is used to store grain or animal feed.
metadata.excludes: interiors of silos or grain bins (6131)

metadata.title: Agricultural building— except silos
metadata.definition: Permanent building of any height used for agricultural operations or storage.
metadata.includes: silo or grain bin exterior, barn, livestock stalls
metadata.excludes: interiors of silos or grain bins (6131)

metadata.title: Mobile building
metadata.definition: Buildings for any use that are constructed with the ability to be moved from one location to another.
metadata.includes: modular or trailer home; sheds; trailers used as offices or classroom; tiny house; portable toilet or spot-a-pot

metadata.title: Building— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Building of known type but does not match codes from 621 through 626.

metadata.title: Structures other than buildings
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify constructed structures that are not buildings, including structures over land and water.
metadata.includes: scaffolding towers, dams, bridges, locks; grandstands, stadia; pools; scaffolds, staging; towers, poles; guardrails, road dividers; hydrants; road signs; railroad tracks; offshore oil platforms
metadata.excludes: interiors of structures defined as confined spaces (61); buildings (62);  silo exterior (624); patios (6624); stairs or steps (661); pedestrian, train and subway tunnels (6124)

metadata.title: Structures other than buildings— unspecified
metadata.definition: Structures other than buildings with too little information to choose a code from 631 to 639.

metadata.title: Offshore oil platform
metadata.definition: Large structure built over bodies of water used for well drilling for petroleum and natural gas. They may be fixed to the ocean floor, consist of an artificial island, or float. Many also contain facilities to accommodate their workforce.
metadata.includes: offshore oil rigs

metadata.title: Bridges, dams, locks
metadata.definition: All types of structural bridges, overpasses, dams, and locks over land or water.
metadata.includes: foot and swinging bridges,  overpass abutments

metadata.title: Structural barriers
metadata.definition: Structure that provides a barrier between two areas.
metadata.includes: guardrails, road dividers, parking blocks, retaining wall, fences and gates

metadata.title: Structural barriers— unspecified
metadata.definition: Structural barrier with too little information to choose a code from 6331 through 6339.

metadata.title: Guardrails, road dividers or barriers
metadata.definition: Permanent or temporary structures used to provide a boundary for a road, parking lot or other outdoor surface usually to prevent access or promote safety. May be composed any material including fencing, concrete, rigid plastic or metal.
metadata.includes: jersey wall, road median, noise barrier, soundwall
metadata.excludes: railings on or in buildings, attached banister, hand rail or balustrade (657), parking barriers (6332)

metadata.title: Parking blocks or barriers
metadata.definition: Small barriers, usually made of concrete, used in parking areas to assist in vehicle parking.
metadata.includes: wheel stops, parking chocks

metadata.title: Retaining wall
metadata.definition: Structures designed to restrain soil to a slope that it would not naturally keep and used to bound soils between two different ground elevations.
metadata.includes: bulkhead, seawall, gravity or piling wall
metadata.excludes: decorative or garden wall (639) building wall (655)

metadata.title: Fences
metadata.definition: Upright barriers made of any material enclosing an area to mark a boundary, control access, or prevent escape.
metadata.includes: Metal fence, wooden fence; electric fences

metadata.title: Gates
metadata.definition: A moveable barrier used to allow or prevent entry or exit from an area, often with a boundary surrounding the area. Can be made of any material and be powered or non powered.
metadata.includes: railroad crossing gate; turnstiles

metadata.title: Structural barriers— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Structural barriers that are known but do not match codes from 6331 through 6335.
metadata.includes: decorative or garden walls; factory and warehouse guardrails; machine guards (9324)

metadata.title: Scaffolds, staging
metadata.definition: All types of scaffolds and staging used inside or outside buildings or other structures either self supported or supported by other means and used as a temporary work platforms. Incidents occurring on the stairs of a scaffold or other structure should be coded as stairs in group 661.
metadata.includes: improvised staging; self-supporting staging; staging supported by structure or other means; catwalks; suspended staging; changes in level or elevation on machine platforms (i.e. steps or stairs)
metadata.excludes: aerial lifts and scissor lifts (3435); forklifts (8621); Fixed machine ladders (6614); Portable ladders (73)

metadata.title: Scaffolds, staging— unspecified
metadata.definition: Scaffolds or staging with too little information to assign a code from 6341 to 6349.

metadata.title: Improvised scaffolds or staging
metadata.definition: Scaffolds or staging constructed of makeshift parts not intended to be used as scaffolding.
metadata.includes: horse scaffolds, saw horse supported work platform

metadata.title: Self-supporting scaffolds or staging
metadata.definition: Scaffolds or staging consisting of one or more platforms designed to be supported by outrigger beams, brackets, poles, legs, uprights, posts, frames, or similar rigid support and able to stand independently.
metadata.includes: wood or extension trestle staging; pole, ladder jack, frame, mobile, roof bracket, pump jack scaffolds; tube and coupler scaffolds

metadata.title: Suspended or hanging scaffolds or staging
metadata.definition: Scaffolding or staging that is supported from overhead with ropes or pulleys.
metadata.includes: Boatswain’s chair; Catenary suspended scaffolds; needle beam, suspension, single-point adjustable, double-point or multiple-point adjustable scaffolds; interior hung suspended scaffolds; float ship suspended scaffolds

metadata.title: Catwalks
metadata.definition: Elevated walkway, platform or open bridge often found in industrial or construction settings.

metadata.title: Scaffolds—staging— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Scaffold or staging that is known but does not match codes 6341 through 6344.
metadata.includes: modeling runway

metadata.title: Towers, poles
metadata.definition: All types of poles, towers, and telecommunication antennae.
metadata.includes: satellite dishes, towers, utility poles, monopoles, radio masts

metadata.title: Towers, poles— unspecified
metadata.definition: Tower or pole with too little information to choose a code from 6351 to 6359.

metadata.title: Telecommunications and cell phone towers
metadata.definition: Towers used to hold telecommunication equipment and antennae.
metadata.includes: mobile cell towers

metadata.title: Utility poles
metadata.definition: Poles supporting telephone, cable TV, fiber optic, internet or electric power lines or supporting area lighting equipment.
metadata.includes: Telephone and electric poles; lamppost; street lights
metadata.excludes: electric power lines (4612); cable TV or internet lines (4612), telecommunications towers (6351)

metadata.title: Road signs, poles— except utility
metadata.definition: An upright structure used as a stay, support or as a decorative element. They can be used to hold signs or signals.
metadata.includes: sign posts; traffic light or sign poles; pillars; columns; posts; bollards; moorings; road signs
metadata.excludes: utility pole (6352); fence post (6334); signs separate from a pole (226); nontraffic signs (226) electrical or electronic signs, except the pole (2242)

metadata.title: Windmills, wind turbines
metadata.definition: Structures that convert wind into rotational energy using propeller like blades. The rotational energy can then be used to power machines or create electricity.

metadata.title: Towers, poles— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Towers or poles that are known but do not match codes 6351 through 6355.
metadata.includes: fire and ranger towers; satellite dishes; antenna
metadata.excludes: power and utility lines (4612); offshore oil platforms (631); oil rigs and derricks (325); other derricks (3427)

metadata.title: Man-made water enclosures
metadata.definition: Structures using man-made building materials, such as concrete or fiberglass, which are closed on all sides and the bottom with an open top used to contain water for recreation or to use as a water source.
metadata.includes: above and below ground swimming pools; man-made ponds; reservoirs
metadata.excludes: reservoirs created by damming a lake or river (671)

metadata.title: Man-made water enclosures— unspecified
metadata.definition: Man-made structures closed on all sides and the bottom with an open top used to contain water for recreation or to use as a water source with too little information to choose code 6361 or 6362.

metadata.title: Swimming pools
metadata.definition: Man-made above ground or in ground swimming pools

metadata.title: Man-made water enclosures— except swimming pools
metadata.definition: Water enclosures constructed with man-made materials closed on all sides and the bottom with an open top used to contain water for recreation or to use as a water source, except swimming pools.
metadata.includes: Ponds and pools (except swimming) made of concrete, fiberglass or other materials, reservoirs; water treatment pools; aquaculture, aquaponics, and hydroponics tanks and pools
metadata.excludes: Reservoirs created by damming a lake or river (671); Manmade lakes and ponds (67)

metadata.title: Excavations, strip mines, and quarries— except confined space
metadata.definition: Non confined space man-made open holes, cavities or pits in the earth created while obtaining raw materials.
metadata.includes: surface or open pit mine; high wall
metadata.excludes: underground mine (6121); trenching excavation (611); mounds or piles of excavated dirt, materials (6631)

metadata.title: Other structures— unspecified
metadata.definition: Other structures not classified in codes 620 to 637 but with too little information to choose a code from 6381 through 6389.

metadata.title: Porches, balconies, decks
metadata.definition: Covered or uncovered structure attached to a building, usually raised off of the ground.
metadata.includes: veranda, terrace, portico

metadata.title: Piers, wharfs, water docks
metadata.definition: Platform supported on pillars or girders leading from the shore into a body of water, often used to moor boats. Also includes floating docks.
metadata.includes: quay, berth; floating docks

metadata.title: Railroad tracks
metadata.definition: Structure consisting of rails, railroad ties and fasteners which provide a surface for rail vehicles to roll upon. Maybe electrified on not.
metadata.includes: railway, light railway, subway tracks

metadata.title: Hydrants
metadata.definition: Fixture with a with a valve and spout by which a hose may be attached to a water main.
metadata.includes: fire hydrant, fire plug

metadata.title: Mailboxes
metadata.definition: Box used to deliver mail or receive mail to be delivered. May be attached to a post, free standing or attached to a structure.
metadata.includes: letterbox, postbox

metadata.title: Stadia, pavilions, stages
metadata.definition: Structures that are not fully enclosed. They may be open to the sides or without a roof.
metadata.includes: Stadia; amphitheaters; grandstands; train stations and platforms

metadata.title: Structures— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Other structures that are known but do not match codes 6381 through 6386.
metadata.includes: concrete planters; decorative fountains;  nautical anchors, buoys or channel markers; movable bleachers; skate park structures; ski jumps

metadata.title: Structures other than buildings— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Structures that are known but do not match codes 631 through 6389.

metadata.title: Building systems
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify the mechanical systems in a building. This category will primarily be used as a secondary source to classify building system complications which produce injuries or illnesses. For example, illnesses produced by foreign particles in the air may be the result of a poor ventilation (climate control) system; illnesses produced by contaminated drinking water may be the result of a poor plumbing system. Parts of building systems are coded in division 3 or 4.
metadata.includes: climate control systems (heating, a/c); plumbing systems
