metadata.excludes: light fixtures (2241); plumbing fixtures (225) electric parts (461); structural parts of a building (65); building appliances (3); security systems (93)

metadata.title: Building systems— unspecified
metadata.definition: Building system with too little information to choose a code from 641 through 649.

metadata.title: Ventilation and climate control systems
metadata.definition: Building system which provides thermal comfort and acceptable indoor air quality and consists of piping, ductwork, heating and/or cooling equipment.
metadata.includes: vents, ducts, thermostats
metadata.excludes: AC unit; fans; blowers;  building furnaces and heaters (3)

metadata.title: Plumbing systems
metadata.definition: Building system which provides water supply and distribution and waste collection and removal. It consists of pipes; plumbing fixtures, drains, and traps.
metadata.includes: water, gas, or sewer system, pipes, drains

metadata.title: Electrical systems
metadata.definition: Building system that provides electrical power including outlets, wiring, and circuits.
metadata.excludes: wire, fuses, circuit boxes (461); lighting fixtures (25)

metadata.title: Building systems— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Building system that is known but does not match codes from 641 through 643.

metadata.title: Other structural elements
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify the separate structural elements that are parts of buildings and other structures. Structural elements should be listed as the source of an injury when applicable regardless of whether they are independent or part of a building.
metadata.includes: doors and door frames; roofs; roof trusses; skylights; ceilings, walls; windows; elevator shafts
metadata.excludes: unattached building materials such as brick or stone (42); unattached structural parts (421); fixed ladders (6614); railroad tracks (6383); floors of buildings (662); stairs and escalators (661) ramps (6621); loading docks or dock plates (658)

metadata.title: Other structural elements— unspecified
metadata.definition: Structural elements where too little information is provided to choose a code from 6510 through 659.

metadata.title: Doors— structurally attached
metadata.definition: Powered and non powered doors of buildings or other structures including both the door itself and the door frame.
metadata.includes: door jamb, garage door, roll up door, revolving doors, powered doors
metadata.excludes: vehicle doors (4721); furniture or fixture doors, separate from the whole (2229); gates (6335)

metadata.title: Doors— unspecified
metadata.definition: Powered and non powered doors of buildings or other structures when a more specific code from 6511 through 6513 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Doors— swinging and sliding
metadata.definition: Doors that either swing or slide horizontally around a pivot or fixed track.

metadata.title: Doors— rail mounted and garage
metadata.definition: Doors that open vertically rising or lowering along a fixed track.
metadata.includes: garage doors; loading dock doors

metadata.title: Doors— rotating
metadata.definition: Doors that rotate around a fixed access.

metadata.title: Windows, openings— structurally attached
metadata.definition: Opening in a wall of a building or other structure.
metadata.includes: casement, sash, window frame, sill, window panes
metadata.excludes: skylight (6531); vehicle windows, attached (8); vehicle window panes, unattached (4); building window panes, unattached (4)

metadata.title: Roofs
metadata.definition: Roofs of any type or material of all buildings and other structures including skylights, existing openings and roof edges.
metadata.excludes: attached vehicle roofs (84); separate vehicle roofs (4726)

metadata.title: Roofs— unspecified
metadata.definition: Roofs of all buildings and other structures with too little information to choose code 6531 or 6532.

metadata.title: Skylights or other existing roof openings
metadata.definition: Opening in any building or other structure's roof. It can be covered with transparent material such as glass to admit light.
metadata.includes: hole in roof, roof window

metadata.title: Roof surface
metadata.definition: All building and other structure roof surfaces of all types not involving a skylight or other existing opening.
metadata.includes: roof edge

metadata.title: Ceilings
metadata.definition: Overhead interior surface of a building or structure that covers the underside of the roof or the floor of the level above. Use this code when source documents say that worker contacted or fell through ceiling.

metadata.title: Walls
metadata.definition: Side of a building or structure that supports the ceiling and roof.
metadata.includes: partial or half walls that are part of the building structure; interior walls, exterior walls
metadata.excludes: partitions and room dividers  (2213); retaining walls (6333); decorative walls (6339)

metadata.title: Trusses, girders, beams—structurally attached
metadata.definition: Rigid framework made of any material used to support a structure and is attached to the structure.
metadata.includes: Roof trusses, joists

metadata.title: Handrails, banisters—structurally attached
metadata.definition: Rail or rod shaped element made of any material attached to a structure in order to create a partial barrier and/or provide a place to hold onto.
metadata.includes: balustrade, parapet, stair railing

metadata.title: Loading docks, dock plates
metadata.definition: Sloped or straight surface used for joining 2 different levels which can be permanent or temporary.
metadata.includes: jet bridge

metadata.title: Structural elements— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Structural elements that are known but do not match codes  from 651 through 658.
metadata.includes: prefabricated building materials, stage sets or scenery
metadata.excludes: partitions and room dividers (2213), retaining walls (6333), decorative walls (6339)

metadata.title: Ground, travel, and support surfaces
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify walking, working, floor, ground, and road surfaces. These surfaces can be made or any material. They can be temporary or permanent, indoors or outdoors, and above or below ground. The can be covered with another material or substance such as tile or grass. Floor surfaces of structures other than buildings (62) or surfaces of confined spaces should be coded as the entire structure or space. If the source of injury is the stairs or fixed ladder of any building, structure or confined space, the appropriate code from group 661 should be selected.
metadata.includes: escalators; floors; ground; sidewalks, paths, outdoor walkways; stairs, steps; streets, roads, driveways; ramps, runways, loading docks; moving walkways; parking lots; airport runways
metadata.excludes: floor surfaces of structures other than buildings or confined spaces  (61, 62)

metadata.title: Ground, travel, and support surfaces— unspecified
metadata.definition: Temporary or permanent walking, working, floor, ground  and road surfaces, either inside or outside, with too little information to choose a code from 6611 through 669.

metadata.title: Stairs, multi level surfaces
metadata.definition: Surfaces with multiple levels that provide gradual access to a different level.
metadata.includes: stairs; steps; escalators
metadata.excludes: changes in level, steps and stairs on machine platforms (661); portable ladders (73)

metadata.title: Stairs, steps
metadata.definition: Stairs or steps, either inside or outside, except ladders, that serve as a surface on which a person is supported.
metadata.includes: indoor stairs, steps; outdoor stairs, steps; uncompleted stairs, such as stringers and risers; stairwell; stair landings
metadata.excludes: moveable ladders (73) fixed ladders or fire escapes (6614), moving walkways (664), step stools (733)

metadata.title: Curbs
metadata.definition: Transitional areas between roads and walkways

metadata.title: Escalators
metadata.definition: Mechanical steps for the transportation of people from one level to another.

metadata.title: Fixed ladder or fire escape
metadata.definition: Ladder or fire escape permanently attached to a structure.
metadata.includes: fire escape platform, steps or structure

metadata.title: Constructed surfaces
metadata.definition: Finished surface used for travel and/or support of any material whether inside a structure or outside. It can be finished with wood, carpeting, tile, vinyl, asphalt, cement, etc. or covered with snow, ice or mud. Floor surfaces of structures other than buildings (63) or surfaces of confined spaces (61) should be coded as the entire structure or space.
metadata.includes: building floor (including basement) surfaces; carpeted or tiled surfaces; wooden floors; pavement; sidewalk; asphalt; road; street; highway; patio; parking lot; driveway; paved trails; surfaces under construction
metadata.excludes: elevator floors (3431); mine floors (6121); scaffold, staging, or temporary work platform surfaces (634); vehicle floors (Division 8); outdoor ground surfaces (663); below ground surfaces such as ditches and trenches (61); piers, wharfs (6382); loading dock (658); moving walkways (664); roofs (653); stairs, steps escalators (661)

metadata.title: Ramps, inclines
metadata.definition: Sloped surface used for joining 2 different levels which can be permanent or temporary.

metadata.title: Existing opening, hole in constructed surface
metadata.definition: Finished surface of any material with a existing opening or hole that contributes to the event.
metadata.includes: trap door, door in floor; pot holes in parking lot or road; drains or grates in the ground; cattle guard; bottom of elevator shaft; bottom of any constructed hole or pit

metadata.title: Constructed surface irregularity
metadata.definition: Finished surface of any material with an irregularity that contributes to the event.
metadata.includes: Crack, fissure, depression or bump in finished surface; transition from one finished surface to another, threshold, paved outdoor surface irregularity; curb on outdoor surface; damaged wall to wall (attached) carpet; speed bumps; loose gravel
metadata.excludes: hole in ground (6634); manhole interiors (6122); unattached carpet (2231)

metadata.title: Other constructed surface
metadata.definition: Finished indoor or outdoor surface without any curbs, irregularities or holes mentioned as contributing to the event. Code here if 6621 through 6623 do not apply.
metadata.includes: smooth pavement or asphalt; floors without an irregularity or hole, parking lots, driveways

metadata.title: Natural surfaces, structures
metadata.definition: Any outdoor area or structure where the surface is left in its natural state, or may be excavated or graded, but unpaved. These may be used as ground surfaces for falls. They may also function as structures that are either naturally occurring (valleys, mountains) or man-made of natural materials (embankments, mulch piles, snow mounds, sink holes) for other types of events. They may be comprised of or covered by rock, dirt, grass or other vegetation, ice, snow or mud.
metadata.includes: trails, parking lots or driveways made of dirt; any outdoor ground surfaces; fields; berms, embankments
metadata.excludes: ditches, channels, trenches, excavations—confined space (611); finished surface (662)

metadata.title: Slopes, embankments
metadata.definition: A steeply sloping area that does not constitute a large rise in elevation
metadata.includes: earth or snow embankment, runaway truck ramp made of earth; pond or river embankments; mounds or unrestrained piles (such as for mulch, gravel, or snow); berms

metadata.title: Hills, mountains
metadata.definition: Natural or man made earth that is elevated above its surrounding earth.
metadata.includes: hills, mountains, cliffs
metadata.excludes: strip mine or quarry excavations, highwalls (637)

metadata.title: Recessed earth structures
metadata.definition: Natural or man made earth that is below its surrounding earth.
metadata.includes: valley; gorge; crevice; canyon; non confined ditch, culvert or trench, larger sinkholes
metadata.excludes: ditches, channels, trenches, excavations—confined space (611); excavations, quarries nonconfined (637)

metadata.title: Hole in ground
metadata.definition: The outdoor ground surface with a hole that contributes to the event.
metadata.includes: hole in lawn or field

metadata.title: Ground irregularity
metadata.definition: The outdoor ground surface with an irregularity other than a hole that contributes to the event.
metadata.includes: natural gravel, rock, pebble or stone covered surface;  bump; depression; transition from ground surface to another surface

metadata.title: Ground
metadata.definition: The outdoor ground surface without any irregularities or holes mentioned as contributing to the event. Code here if descriptions of 6631 through 6635 do not apply.
metadata.includes: surface of the earth covered by dirt,  grass, ice, snow or mud; sand surfaces (e.g. riding ring, baseball field)

metadata.title: Moving walkways
metadata.definition: Slow-moving conveyor mechanism that transports people across a horizontal or inclined plane over a short to medium distance.
metadata.includes: autowalk, people-mover, moving sidewalk

metadata.title: Ground, travel and support surfaces— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Surfaces that are known but do not match codes 6611 through 664.
metadata.excludes: vehicle interior floors (4739); machine and vehicle platforms and support surfaces (4726)

metadata.title: Bodies of water
metadata.definition: Part of the earth's surface that is naturally covered with water.
metadata.includes: lake; ponds; ocean; bay; channel; waterway; sea
metadata.excludes: If water is not present, select code from ground surfaces (66)

metadata.title: Bodies of water— unspecified
metadata.definition: Bodies of water with too little information to choose a code from 671 through 679.

metadata.title: Ponds, lakes
metadata.definition: Ponds and lakes that either occur naturally or were created due to damming a water source or digging
metadata.includes: Natural and man-made lakes and ponds; reservoirs or lakes created by dams; water filled quarries
metadata.excludes: swimming pools; concrete or fiberglass ponds or tanks (636)

metadata.title: Rivers, streams
metadata.definition: Natural body of water that flows across the earth.
metadata.includes: creek; tributary; rapids; fall lines; canal

metadata.title: Coastal waters
metadata.definition: Coastal bodies of deep salt and brackish water
metadata.includes: sounds, bays, gulfs, intercoastal waterway

metadata.title: Oceans, seas
metadata.definition: Large natural body of salt water.
metadata.includes: sea, ocean shipping channels

metadata.title: Bodies of water— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Natural water body that is known but does not match codes 670 through 674. Includes shallow wetland areas.
metadata.includes: swamps, marshes, wetlands

metadata.title: Structures and surfaces— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Structure, surface or structural element that is known but does not match codes 61 through 679.

metadata.title: TOOLS, INSTRUMENTS, AND EQUIPMENT
metadata.definition: Codes in this division classify tools, instruments and equipment used in any industry that are not machines or vehicles.  If a part that produces an injury is attached to a tool (e.g., a saw blade or drill bit) then the entire tool should be listed as the source, unless the injury was inflicted by the electrical cord. If a part is known to be unattached and independent of a tool—or if it is probable that the tool is not involved in the injury—then that specific part (Division 4) should be listed as the source. If a tool or equipment is operated autonomously or robotically, it should be coded in Davison 3.
metadata.includes: all handtools; ladders; medical and surgical instruments and equipment; photographic equipment; protective equipment (except clothing); recreation and athletic equipment; clocks; cooking and eating utensils; firearms and other weapons; musical instruments; sewing notions; writing, drawing, and art supplies
metadata.excludes: containers, furniture and fixtures (2); machinery (3); parts and materials (4)

metadata.title: Tools, instruments, and equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Objects that are known to be tools, instruments or equipment but with too little information to choose a more specific code from this division.

metadata.title: Handtools
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classifies all nonpowered and powered handtools which are handheld and operated. The tools can be powered by electricity, fuel (gasoline, coal), air, steam, water, or gunpowder. They are classified according to their common functions  (e.g., boring, cutting, digging, gripping, etc.) If a drill bit, saw blade, or other tool part that produces an injury is attached to a handtool then the entire handtool should be listed as the source, unless the injury was inflicted by an electrical cord. If the part is separate, a code from Division 4 should be selected.
metadata.includes: cutting handtools; digging handtools; gripping handtools; measuring handtools; striking and nailing handtools; surfacing handtools; turning handtools; cleaning handtools; crowbars; pitchforks; rakes; stapling tools
metadata.excludes: machinery (3); unattached drill bits, saw blades and other separated parts of tools (464); hoisting accessories (45); fasteners such as nails, screws, nuts, and bolts (441); autonomous or robotic tools (3)

metadata.title: Handtools— unspecified
metadata.definition: Objects known to be handtools but with too little information to choose a code from 7110 through 7199.

metadata.title: Boring handtools
metadata.definition: Powered or nonpowered handtools which are commonly used to make holes using an attached revolving bit.
metadata.includes: augers; braces; drills
metadata.excludes: unattached drill bits (464); boring and drilling machinery (3); upright drill presses (3531)

metadata.title: Boring handtools— unspecified
metadata.definition: Boring handtools with too little information to choose a code from 7111 through 7119.

metadata.title: Plumbing augers, snakes
metadata.definition: Handtool with a spiral shaft used for boring holes or moving loose material.
metadata.includes: Plumbing augers, corkscrews, bores, counterbores, breast augers, wimbles

metadata.title: Drills, braces, drivers
metadata.definition: Handtool with an edged or pointed end for making holes in hard substances by revolving or by a succession of blows.
metadata.includes: breast drills, gimlets, hand drills, pin vises, push drills, reamers, ratchet drills powered countersinks, pneumatic drills, cordless drills, variable speed drills, bit braces, brace and bits, joist braces; impact drills; impact drivers

metadata.title: Routers, molders
metadata.definition: Handtool with a revolving vertical spindle and cutter for milling out surfaces.

metadata.title: Awls, punches
metadata.definition: Handtool used to punch a hole or make an impression in a material.
metadata.includes: counterpunches, belt punches, countersinks, center punches; hole punches

metadata.title: Boring handtools— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Boring handtools that are known but do not match codes 7111 through 7114.
metadata.includes: bodkins (make holes in cloth)

metadata.title: Cutting handtools
metadata.definition: Sharp-edged, powered or nonpowered handtools which are commonly used to penetrate and separate objects or materials.
metadata.includes: axes, hatchets; bolt cutters; knives; saws; scissors, snips, shears; electric cutters; weed trimmers
metadata.excludes: sawing machinery (355); unattached saw blades (4642); spokeshaves, shavehooks (7164); putty knives (7166); scalpels and surgical knives (7412); pick axes (7132)

metadata.title: Cutting handtools— unspecified
metadata.definition: Cutting handtools with too little information to choose a code from 7121 through 7129.

metadata.title: Chainsaws
metadata.definition: Portable powered saw that has teeth linked together to form an endless chain.

metadata.title: Saws— except chainsaws
metadata.definition: Handtool used to cut hard material and usually equipped with a toothed blade or disk.
metadata.includes: fret, turning, cross-cut, veneer, hand, circular, bow, hack, scroll, coping, or jig saws; backsaws

metadata.title: Box cutters, razor knives
metadata.definition: Cutting handtool that typically consists of a retractable razor blade in a thin metal or plastic sheath.
metadata.includes: razor blades, drywall knives, utility knives

metadata.title: Knives
metadata.definition: Cutting handtool consisting of a sharp blade fastened to a handle.
metadata.includes: bayonets, mat cutters, palette knives, bushwhackers, steak and butcher knives, potato peelers, carving and pocket knives, pushknives, cleavers, scrapers (used with lathes), daggers, scythes, detail and shaping knives, dowel makers (used with lathes), shavers, sickles, drawknives, spears, gouges, stilettos, groovers, switchblades, hacks, swords, hunting knives, table knives, inshavers, whittling knives, knife blades, veiners, lances, woodcarving knives, linoleum knives, woodturning tools (used with lathes), machetes, marking knives, unspecified knives; cutting mandolin
metadata.excludes: razor blades, drywall knives, utility knives (7123)

metadata.title: Scissors, snips, shears
metadata.definition: Cutting handtool having two blades whose cutting edges slide past each other.
metadata.includes: grass clippers, hedge clippers or trimmers; pruning shears; hand, school, barber's, or tailor's scissors; tin snips

metadata.title: Lawn edgers, trimmers
metadata.definition: Cutting handtools used for trimming grass, especially at the edges. Some use a monofilament string to cut, while others use a blade and a wheel.
metadata.includes: weed trimmers, weed whackers, sod cutters

metadata.title: Axes, hatchets
metadata.definition: Cutting handtool that consists of a heavy edged head fixed parallel to a handle.
metadata.includes: adzes, froes, grub axes, bark spuds, halberds, battle axes, hatchets, broad axes, poleaxes, tomahawks, celts, stone axe

metadata.title: Bolt cutters
metadata.definition: Handtool used for cutting chains, padlocks, bolts and wire mesh. It typically has long handles and short blades, with compound hinges to maximize leverage and cutting force.
metadata.includes: bolt cutters, pliers—cutting, chain cutters, wire cutters, lock cutters

metadata.title: Cutting handtools— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Cutting handtools which are known but do not match codes 7121 through 7128.
metadata.includes: Combination tools that include cutting - sledge axe; multi-hand tool (Leatherman); electric razors, clippers; can openers; hand-operated paper cutters; chasers (cut screw threads); glass cutters; wedges; letter openers; nail clippers

metadata.title: Digging and material moving handtools
metadata.definition: Powered or nonpowered handtools which are commonly used for turning up, loosening, or removing earth.
metadata.includes: hoes; picks; shovels; trowels; post hole diggers

metadata.title: Digging and material moving handtools — unspecified
metadata.definition: Digging and earth moving handtools with too little information to choose a code from 7131 through 7139.

metadata.title: Hoes
metadata.definition: Long-handled handtool with a thin metal blade, used mainly for weeding and breaking up soil.
metadata.includes: garden, masons, grub or scuffle hoes

metadata.title: Picks
metadata.definition: Handtool consisting of a long handle with a curved metal bar with a point at one end and a chisel edge or point at the other, used for breaking up hard ground or rock.
metadata.includes: axe picks, ice picks, mattocks (combination adze and axe)

metadata.title: Shovels
metadata.definition: Long-handled handtool with a broad flat blade and typically upturned sides, used for moving material.
metadata.includes: snow shovels, spades

metadata.title: Trowels
metadata.definition: Handtool with a flat, pointed blade, used to apply and spread mortar or plaster or with a curved scoop for lifting plants or earth.
metadata.includes: hand scoops, garden trowels, spuds (combination trowel and chisel)

metadata.title: Rakes, pitchforks
metadata.definition: Handtool with a handle and a crossbar toothed like a comb at the end or with sharp prongs or tines. It is used for gathering, lifting or throwing loose material such as grass or leaves, or for smoothing loose soil or gravel.
metadata.includes: garden, swimming pool, and leaf rakes; garden, manure, and hay forks; spading forks

metadata.title: Digging and material moving handtools— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Digging and earth moving handtools that are known but do not match codes 7131 through 7135.
metadata.includes: dibbles (make seed holes in garden), post hole diggers, augers

metadata.title: Gripping and turning handtools
metadata.definition: Powered or nonpowered handtools which are commonly used for clutching, squeezing, gripping or turning objects.
metadata.includes: pliers, tongs; vises, clamps; gear pullers; screwdrivers, ratchet drivers, and wrenches
metadata.excludes: lathes (3534); clamps used as fasteners (4411); hooks (bush, grass, baling, and husking), grappling irons and hooks, anchors, cant hooks (452); peavies (7199); medical implements (749)

metadata.title: Gripping and turning handtools— unspecified
metadata.definition: Gripping and turning handtools with too little information to choose a code from 7141 through 7149.

metadata.title: Pliers
metadata.definition: Handtool pincers with parallel, flat, and typically serrated surfaces, used chiefly for gripping objects or bending wire.
metadata.includes: forceps—excluding medical, tweezers, nippers, ice tongs, pincers, oyster tongs, pliers, vise grips

metadata.title: Vises, clamps
metadata.definition: A vise is a handtool with movable jaws that are used to hold an object in place and a clamp is a brace, band, or clasp used for strengthening or holding things together.
metadata.includes: handscrews; bench dogs; spreaders clamps; bench screws; spring, edging, hand, band, toggle, pipe, cam or bar clamps; bench, front or miter vises

metadata.title: Tongs
metadata.definition: Handtool with two movable arms that are joined at one end, used for picking up and holding things.
metadata.includes: utility tongs; furnace tongs
metadata.excludes: Kitchen tongs (719); rig tongs, power tongs (3256)

metadata.title: Wrenches, ratchets
metadata.definition: Handtool used to provide grip and mechanical advantage in applying torque to turn objects or keep them from turning.
metadata.includes: spanners, open-end wrenches, adjustable, pipe, Allen, socket, box, spark-plug wrenches, monkey, and tuning wrenches; air wrenches; impact wrenches; ratchet wrench

metadata.title: Screwdrivers
metadata.definition: Handtool with a handle and a shaft ending in a tip that is put into the screw head in order to turn it to tighten or loosen the screw.
metadata.includes: Phillips head screwdriver, straight tip screwdriver, electric screwdrivers, rechargeable screwdrivers

metadata.title: Gripping and turning handtools— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Gripping and turning handtools that are known but do not match  codes 7141 through 7145.
metadata.includes: nutcrackers; wheel, gear or bearing pullers; bolt setters; unattached hand crank

metadata.title: Striking and nailing handtools
metadata.definition: Powered and nonpowered handtools which are commonly used for delivering blows or strokes, or for nailing.
metadata.includes: hammers; mallets; countersinks; sledges

metadata.title: Striking and nailing handtools— unspecified
metadata.definition: Striking and nailing handtools with too little information to choose a code from 7151 through 7159.

metadata.title: Jackhammers
metadata.definition: Portable pneumatic electro-mechanical handtool that combines a hammer directly with a chisel.
metadata.includes: pile driving hammers, jackhammers, steam hammers

metadata.title: Sledges, sledgehammers
metadata.definition: Handtool with a large, flat head, attached to a long handle that allows it to gather momentum during a swing and apply a large force compared to regular hammers.
metadata.includes: maul

metadata.title: Riveters
metadata.definition: Handtool used to drive a permanent fastener with a head on one end into a punched or drilled hole and flatten the other end to secure it in place.
metadata.includes: electric riveting hammers, pneumatic or electric riveters, powered riveters

metadata.title: Nailing or stapling tools
metadata.definition: Handtool used to shoot and drive nails or staples into another material.
metadata.includes: pneumatic nail or staple guns, point drivers, electric nail or staple guns, guns, gunpowder activated nail or staple guns, manual staplers

metadata.title: Chisels
metadata.definition: Long-bladed hand tool with a beveled cutting edge and a handle that is struck with a hammer or mallet, used to cut or shape hard materials.
metadata.includes: bench chisels, mortise chisels, cold chisels, paring chisels, socket chisels, corner chisels, steel chisels, deep-mortise chisels, dog leg chisels, socket slicks, dovetail chisels, slicks

metadata.title: Toe kickers, knee kickers
metadata.definition: Handtool used for stretching carpet into corners without leaving wrinkles or bulges and getting a tight fit.
metadata.includes: carpet kickers

metadata.title: Other hammers, mallets
metadata.definition: Handtool consisting of a weighted head fixed to a longer handle that is swung to deliver impact to a small area.
metadata.includes: ball-peen, meat, cabinetmaker, tack, claw or framer hammers;  air hammers, electric hammers, electric chipping hammers; mallets—gavels, printer’s, beechwood, rawhide, carver’s, rubber, or cocobolo mallets

metadata.title: Striking and nailing handtools— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Striking and nailing handtools that are known but do not match codes 7151 through 7157.
metadata.includes: beetles, staffs, staves, tampers, hand-threshing flails
metadata.excludes: law enforcement batons, night sticks, clubs (7831)

metadata.title: Surfacing handtools
metadata.definition: Powered and nonpowered handtools which are commonly used to plane, shape, or make smooth surfaces.
metadata.includes: files (surfacing handtools); planes; sanders; sharpening stones and wheels; cement trowels polishers, and waxers; powered hand grinders; powered sanders
metadata.excludes: sandblasting machinery (3544); planing machinery (353); grinding, polishing machinery (354); drawknives, gouges and groovers (woodcarving chisels), inshavers, veiners, and pushknives (7124)

metadata.title: Surfacing handtools— unspecified
metadata.definition: Surfacing tools with too little information to choose a code from 7161 through 7169.

metadata.title: Grinders— handtool
metadata.definition: Handtool with an abrasive surface used for grinding and polishing materials.
metadata.includes: bench grinders, waterstone grinders, electric grinders, pneumatic grinders, wet/dry grinders, snagging grinders

metadata.title: Sanders— handtool
metadata.definition: Handtool used to smooth surfaces by abrasion with sandpaper that is attached to the sander. Also includes the sandpaper itself.
metadata.includes: handheld power sanders; abrasive pads, sanding sticks, hand sanders, sandpaper, sanding grips, steel wool

metadata.title: Files—surfacing handtool
metadata.definition: Handtool with a rough surface, typically of steel, used for smoothing or shaping a hard material.
metadata.includes: emery boards; round, needle, wood, bastard, cabinet, diamond or detail files; cabinet, keyway, round, or needle rasps; nail files; sculptor’s rasps; rifflers

metadata.title: Planes—surfacing handtool
metadata.definition: Handtool with a sharp blade that is used for smoothing, flattening, shaping and reducing thickness of material.
metadata.includes: cornering tools; jack, jointer, bench, rabbet, block, router, bullnose, scraping, butt mortise, scrub, combination, smoothing, compass, trimming, fore, and hollowing planes; cabinet scrapers,  shavehooks, spokeshaves

metadata.title: Sharpening stones and wheels
metadata.definition: Handtool used to sharpen the edges of tools and implements through grinding and honing.
metadata.includes: corundum or pumice stone,  emery wheels, slipstones, honing stones, water stones, multi-stones, whetstone oilstone

metadata.title: Scrapers
metadata.definition: Handtool used for scraping or removing unwanted matter such as dirt, paint or ice from a surface.
metadata.includes: paint or wallpaper scraper; ice scraper; putty knives

metadata.title: Surfacing handtools— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Surfacing tools that are known but do not match codes  7161 through 7166.
metadata.includes: rotary rasps,  bench strops, scouring pads, sharpening straps

metadata.title: Cleaning handtools
metadata.definition: Powered or non powered equipment used for cleaning.

metadata.title: Cleaning handtools— unspecified
metadata.definition: Powered or non powered equipment used for cleaning with too little information to choose a code from 7171 through 7179.

metadata.title: Buffers, polishers, waxers, scrubbers
metadata.definition: Powered or pushed equipment used to polish, refinish or clean surfaces, especially floors.
metadata.includes: hand held buffing machines, powered polishers, floor buffers and scrubbers, polishing heads
metadata.excludes: industrial or riding buffers and scrubbers (333) robotic buffers, polishers, waxers or scrubbers (3338)

metadata.title: Handled cleaning tools, brooms, mops
metadata.definition: Non-powered handtools used for cleaning surfaces.
metadata.includes: hand, push or straw brooms; pool leaf skimmers and brushes;  ram rods (cleaning rods);  feather dusters; plungers; mops

metadata.title: Vacuum cleaners
metadata.definition: Device that uses suction to remove and collect debris from surfaces for later disposal. They can be hand held or pushed along a surface.
metadata.includes: sweeper, vacuum
metadata.excludes: Industrial or riding vacuum (3335) street cleaning trucks (893); robotic floor cleaners (3338)

metadata.title: Cleaning handtools— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Powered or non powered equipment used for cleaning that is known but does not match codes from 7171 through 7173.
metadata.includes: cleaning brushes and rags; steel brushes; sponges

metadata.title: Welding and heating handtools
metadata.definition: Powered hand-held welding tools which are used to solder, weld, or burn.
metadata.includes: welding, cutting, and blow torches; soldering irons; heat guns; electric burn-in knives; woodburning pens
metadata.excludes: welding and soldering fumes (13); irons (3323); laser cutting machinery (3592); robotic welding machinery (3595); welding machinery (3598)

metadata.title: Welding and heating handtools— unspecified
metadata.definition: Welding and heating handtools with too little information to choose a code from 7181 through 7189.

metadata.title: Torches— welding, cutting
metadata.definition: Handtool that uses gases and a flame to heat metal in order to cut it or join metals together.
metadata.includes: cutting, propane, welding and Mapp torches; welding guns

metadata.title: Soldering irons
metadata.definition: Handtool used for melting solder and using it to connect metal objects. It is composed of a heated metal tip and an insulated handle.
metadata.includes: burning systems, soldering tips, guns, tools, tiplets, coppers or irons; electric burn-in knives; woodburning sets or pens

metadata.title: Heat guns
metadata.definition: Handtool that emits a stream of hot air and used for stripping paint, shrinking wrap and tubing, drying wood, bending plastic, softening adhesives and thawing frozen pipes.
metadata.includes: glue guns

metadata.title: Personal care heat equipment
metadata.definition: Hand held or stationary equipment that uses heat to curl, straighten or dry hair or dry nail polish.
metadata.includes: curling irons and hair straighteners; nail dryers; hair dryers; hand dryers

metadata.title: Blow torches— except welding
metadata.definition: Fuel-burning handtool used for applying controlled flame and heat to various applications
metadata.includes: kitchen blow torches

metadata.title: Welding and heating handtools—  n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Welding and heating handtools that are known but do not match code 7181 through 7185.

metadata.title: Other handtools
metadata.definition: Powered and nonpowered handtools that do not fit coding categories from 711 through 718.

metadata.title: Other handtools— unspecified
metadata.definition: Powered and nonpowered handtools that do not fit coding categories from 711 through 718 and  with too little information to choose a code from 7191 through 7199.

metadata.title: Handheld paint guns, sprayers
metadata.definition: Handtool that uses compressed air or other gases that are pressurized mechanically to apply paint or other finishes through a nozzle.
metadata.includes: airbrush

metadata.title: Cooking and eating utensils— except knives
metadata.definition: All utensils, except knives, used to prepare food or consume it.
metadata.includes: bottle openers; spatulas; forks, spoons; kitchen utensils; skewers; rolling pins; cookie cutters or presses; kitchen tongs

metadata.title: Push-pull rams
metadata.definition: Handtool used with a hydraulic pump to pull, bend and straighten metal.

metadata.title: Crowbars
metadata.definition: Metal handtool with a flattened, curved end to be used as a lever to force 2 objects apart or to remove nails using a fissure on one or both of the ends of the tool.
metadata.includes: nail pullers, prying bars, pinch bars (large crowbars), wrecking bars, breaker bar

metadata.title: Tape guns, dispensers
metadata.definition: Hand held device that dispenses tape, helping it to be applied to a surface and allowing for convenient cut off.
metadata.includes: label gun

metadata.title: Multiple handtools
metadata.definition: A combination of two or more handtools from 7191 through 7199.
metadata.includes: hammer and screwdriver; vacuum cleaner and mop

metadata.title: Other handtools— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Powered and nonpowered handtools that are known but do not match coding categories from 711 through 718 or codes 7191 through 7198.
metadata.includes: flashlights; plate joiners; caulking guns, paint rollers, brushes or sticks; grease guns; hawks (mortar holders); log handling peavies; jig; keys; safety guides; staple removers; padlocks

metadata.title: Measurement and scientific devices
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify devices which are commonly used to determine measurements.
metadata.includes: calipers, micrometers; dividers; gauges; levels; plumb bobs; rulers, tape measures; squares; scales; thermometers; clock; timers; test tubes
metadata.excludes: diagnostic machinery (362); measuring cups (215); measuring spoons (7192); compasses and protractors (799)

metadata.title: Measurement and scientific devices— unspecified
metadata.definition: Measuring devices with too little information to choose a code from 721 through 729.

metadata.title: Laboratory equipment
metadata.definition: Equipment used in a laboratory setting used for measuring materials.
metadata.includes: test tubes; flasks; titration equipment; beakers

metadata.title: Calipers, micrometers
metadata.definition: Device used to measure distance between two opposite sides of an object. Many permit reading out a measurement on a ruled scale, a dial, or a digital display, but can be as simple as a compass with inward or outward-facing point
metadata.includes: dial, vernier, inside, yankee, micrometer and outside calipers; micrometers

metadata.title: Gauges
metadata.definition: Device used for measuring the magnitude, amount, or contents of something, typically with a visual display of such information.
metadata.includes: center finders; multi, dovetail, profile, marking, and scoring gauges

metadata.title: Levels, plumb bobs
metadata.definition: Measuring devices used for establishing vertical or horizontal planes and measuring their evenness.
metadata.includes: spirit levels; plumbs; plummet

metadata.title: Rulers, tape measures
metadata.definition: Measuring device consisting of a straight strip or cylinder of rigid material, typically marked at regular intervals, to draw straight lines or measure distances.
metadata.includes: angle finders; shop, bench, steel, parallel, centering rules, foot and pocket rules; size sticks; straight edges; metersticks; tape lines; tape measures; triangles; rulers; yardsticks; line gauge

metadata.title: Guiding tools
metadata.definition: Measuring device consisting of two straight edges set at right angles to each other, used for checking the correctness of right angles and as a guide for drawing lines on materials before cutting.
metadata.includes: bevels; combination builders tools, speed squares; miter box; framing, T, engineers, try and combination squares

metadata.title: Scales
metadata.definition: Device for determining weight of an object or substance.
metadata.includes: bathroom or kitchen scales; laboratory cups

metadata.title: Clocks
metadata.definition: Devices of any size that tell time whether wind up, electric, digital or analog that are not worn by a person.
metadata.includes: office clocks, cuckoo clocks, ships clocks, travel alarm clocks, and standing clocks; timers
metadata.excludes: clock radios (7524); wrist and pocket watches (9119)

metadata.title: Measurement and scientific devices— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Measuring handtools that are known but do not match  codes from 721 through 728.
metadata.includes: balances, sextants, pantographs, magnetic compasses, thermometers, voltage testers

metadata.title: Portable ladders and stairs
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify movable ladders of any construction: wooden, steel, aluminum, plastic, etc. Movable ladders are portable, foldable, or extendable.
metadata.includes: extension, straight, step and truck-mounted ladders; aerial ladder trams
metadata.excludes: attached attic ladders, fixed ladders or fire escapes (6614); stairs or steps (6611)

metadata.title: Portable ladders and stairs— unspecified
metadata.definition: Moveable ladders with too little information to choose a code from 731 through 739.

metadata.title: Extension ladders
metadata.definition: Non-self-supporting portable ladder that is adjustable in length, consisting of two or more sections that travel lengthwise next to each other to permit length adjustment.

metadata.title: Straight ladders
metadata.definition: Non-self-supporting, rigid portable ladder consisting of a set of vertical rungs and cannot be adjusted for length.

metadata.title: Step ladders
metadata.definition: Self supporting, foldable ladder with an A frame and a small platform at the top. One side has flat steps and the other is a frame to support the ladder.
metadata.includes: folding ladders, stiles, step stools

metadata.title: Multipurpose ladders
metadata.definition: Portable ladders that can be used in multiple configurations including straight, extension and step. They can be self supporting or not.

metadata.title: Truck mounted ladders, aerial ladder trams
metadata.definition: Movable ladders attached to trucks or other vehicles.
metadata.includes: fire truck ladders, utility truck ladders

metadata.title: Portable stairs
metadata.includes: airplane stairs

metadata.title: Portable ladders and stairs— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Movable ladders that are known but do not match codes from 731 through 736.
metadata.includes: ladder assemblies-combination work stands; rope ladders

metadata.title: Medical, dental, and surgical instruments and equipment
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify all medical, surgical, ophthalmic, orthopedic, dental and veterinary instruments and equipment except machinery and furniture.
metadata.includes: hypodermic needles and syringes; surgical knives (scalpels); medical forceps and retractors
metadata.excludes: oxygen tanks (2124); laser cutting machinery (3592); medical machinery, except x-ray (362); x-ray machinery (3621); respirators (923); hospital beds (744); operating tables (2224)

metadata.title: Medical, dental, and surgical instruments and equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Medical and surgical instruments and equipment with too little information to choose a code from 7410 through 749.

metadata.title: Medical sharp instruments
metadata.definition: Needles, syringes, and scalpels—commonly referred to as sharps—used in the medical field.
metadata.includes: suture needles for stitching animals or humans; hypodermic needles or syringes for injecting or removing fluids from animals or humans

metadata.title: Medical sharp instruments— unspecified
metadata.definition: Medical sharps with too little information to choose a code from 7411 through 7419.

metadata.title: Needles, syringes
metadata.definition: Needles used to administer substances through injection into animals and humans or removing fluids from them,  either attached to a syringe or separate. Needles used to stitch open skin of humans or animals.
metadata.includes: hypodermic needles or syringes; suture needles

metadata.title: Scalpels
metadata.definition: Surgical knives used only in the medical field.
metadata.includes: surgical knives; scalpels

metadata.title: Medical sharp instruments— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Medical sharps that are known but do not match codes 7411 or 7412.
metadata.includes: lancets, fingerstick devices

metadata.title: Health care and orthopedic equipment
metadata.definition: Structural devices designed to stabilize, protect or correct problems of the musculoskeletal system.

metadata.title: Health care and orthopedic equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Health care and orthopedic equipment with too little information to choose a code from 7421 through 7429.

metadata.title: Canes, crutches, walkers
metadata.definition: Equipment that provides support and stability to aid in walking.
metadata.includes: walking stick

metadata.title: Corrective or supportive devices
metadata.definition: Devices worn on the body to provide support or correct a medical issue.
metadata.includes: corsets; supporters; compression garments; trusses, orthopedic braces; dentures; prosthetic devices; medical back belts
metadata.excludes: industrial back support belts (9223); athletic supporters (9219)

metadata.title: Health care and orthopedic equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Health care and orthopedic equipment that is known but does not match codes from 7421 or 7422.
metadata.includes: physical therapy equipment; heat packs and pads, ice packs
metadata.excludes: test tubes, vials (721); treadmills other exercise machines (772)

metadata.title: Wheelchairs, mobility devices
metadata.definition: Nonmotorized and motorized wheelchairs as well as motorized shopping carts and mobility scooters that function similar to motorized wheelchairs.

metadata.title: Wheelchairs, mobility devices— unspecified
metadata.definition: Wheelchairs and other mobility devices when it is unknown if powered or nonpowered.

metadata.title: Wheelchairs, scooters— powered
metadata.definition: Powered mobility devices.
metadata.includes: motorized shopping carts

metadata.title: Wheelchairs, scooters— nonpowered
metadata.definition: Nonpowered mobility devices.
metadata.includes: knee scooters

metadata.title: Other mobility devices— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Wheelchairs and other mobility devices that are known but do not match codes 7531 or 7532.
metadata.includes: stair chairs

metadata.title: Medical beds, stretchers, cots
metadata.definition: Beds or stretchers used for patient care and transport. They are typically characterized by being wheeled/mobile, having adjustable height and/or head and foot positioning; guardrails; and/or apparatus for attaching other medical equipment (e.g. IV poles, monitors).
metadata.includes: cots used as wheeled stretchers; hospital beds, cots; backboards, gurneys; break-away beds; exam and operating tables; hospital cribs

metadata.title: Patient hoists, lifting harnesses
metadata.definition: Device that assists in transferring patients and people with limited mobility from one place to another by the use of electrical or hydraulic power.
metadata.includes: patient lift slings; Hoyer lift; draw sheets

metadata.title: Intravenous (IV) poles, pumps and monitors
metadata.definition: Medical device that delivers fluids, such as nutrients and medications, into the veins of a patient's body in controlled amounts and all parts of that device.

metadata.title: Dental handpieces
metadata.definition: Tools used for oral care in a dental clinic setting
metadata.includes: Dental probes; dental extraction tools; dental drills; forceps; cauterizers; dental burs

metadata.title: Medical, dental, and surgical instruments and equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Medical, surgical and dental instruments that are known but do not match codes 741 through 746.
metadata.includes: Medical and dental lab special equipment; Otoscope; forceps; cauterizers; retractors; forceps speculums; stethoscopes;  trephines; feeding tube; catheter; thermometers; surgical lasers; bandages, latex bandages; elastic wrap bandages

metadata.title: Media, office, and business equipment
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify audio/visual and photographic equipment, office and business machines and computer equipment.
metadata.excludes: photographic and copying solutions (19); x-ray machinery and equipment (3621); firearms and other law enforcement and self-defense equipment (78);  athletic clothing and footwear–excluding skis and skates (911); recreational and commercial fishing equipment (777)

metadata.title: Media, office, and business equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Audio/visual, computer and business machinery, equipment and supplies with too little information to choose a code from 7510 through 759.

metadata.title: Personal electronic devices
metadata.definition: Electronic items designed to be used by a single person either portably or at a work station.

metadata.title: Personal electronic devices— unspecified
metadata.definition: Electronic items designed to be used by a single person either portably or at a work station when a more specific code from 7511 through 7519 cannot be determined

metadata.title: Phones, communication devices— wired and wireless
metadata.definition: All types of wired and cellular phones and auxiliary devices.
metadata.includes: mobile or cell phones, PDAs; pagers; wired desk phones; try equipment; answering machines

metadata.title: Laptops, tablets
metadata.definition: Portable foldable keyboard and screen computers or touchscreen devices without a keyboard.

metadata.title: Audio headphones
metadata.definition: Devices worn in or over the ears to transmit sound, either via wire or wirelessly.
metadata.includes: Earphones, earbuds; headsets; headphones
metadata.excludes: Hearing protection headphones (9226); VR equipment (7514); video cameras (7523); video games (792)

metadata.title: Virtual reality (VR) headsets
metadata.definition: Special electronic equipment, such as a helmet with a screen or gloves with sensors, used to interact with a computer-generated simulation of a three-dimensional image or environment.
metadata.includes: VR headset or googles; VR treadmills; VR hand controllers or gloves; VR software; augmented reality equipment

metadata.title: Computer keyboards, mice, laptop trackpads
metadata.definition: Data entry devices used to select characters to input into a computer. May be attached or separate from the entire computer.
metadata.includes: Typewriters and word processing equipment

metadata.title: Multiple personal electronic devices
metadata.definition: Combinations of items from two or more codes from 7511 through 7515.

metadata.title: Personal electronic devices— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Electronic items designed to be used by a single person either portably or at a work station that does not meet the definitions of codes 7511 through 7518.

metadata.title: Computer and media equipment
metadata.definition: Computer and electronic equipment designed for audio, video, data processing, gaming and specialized lighting. Most items in this group are not designed for personal, portable use.

metadata.title: Computer and media equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Computer and electronic equipment designed for audio, video, data processing, gaming and specialized lighting where a more specific code from 7521 through 7529 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: AV equipment

metadata.title: Computers— Desktop, towers, servers
metadata.definition: Computers and servers designed for use at a single location.
metadata.includes: all-in-ones; video display terminals (VDTs); cathode ray tubes (CRTs); computer processing units (CPUs) and towers; servers; mainframe computers
metadata.excludes: laptops and tablets (7512); computer monitors or screens (7522)

metadata.title: Televisions, monitors, electronic screens
metadata.definition: Electronic screens used for viewing computer or video content.
metadata.includes: TV set, smart TV; projection televisions; Smartboard

metadata.title: Cameras, photography equipment— except phone cameras
metadata.definition: Stand-alone photographic cameras and related accessories and equipment used to capture both still and motion picture.
metadata.includes: digital, aerial, movie, box, pinhole, candid, portrait, folding, reflex, hand, still, television, video, and motion-picture cameras; identity recorders; lenses; flashbulbs; tripods; selfie sticks

metadata.title: Audio equipment
metadata.definition: Electronic devices which are used to transmit, receive, play, and record audio-only communications and materials.
metadata.includes: clock radios; stereos; turntables; microphones, speakers; radios; amplifiers; equalizers; tape recorders; dictation machines

metadata.title: Projectors; theatrical lighting equipment
metadata.definition: Devices that project light or images onto a surface using light shone through a lens.
metadata.includes: home theater projectors; cinema projectors; spotlights

metadata.title: Multiple computer and media equipment
metadata.definition: Combinations of items from two or more codes from 7521 through 7529.

metadata.title: Computer and media equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Computer and electronic equipment designed for audio, video, data processing, gaming and specialized lighting where the item does not meet the definition of codes  7521 through 7525.
metadata.includes: video gaming systems --except VR headsets; DVD players

metadata.title: Document handling equipment
metadata.definition: Equipment used for printing, scanning, copying and shredding documents.
metadata.includes: FAX machines; photocopiers; computer printers and plotter; scanners; shredders

metadata.title: Document handling equipment and materials— unspecified
metadata.definition: Document handling equipment with too little information to choose a code from 7531 through 7539.

metadata.title: Printers and plotters—computer
metadata.definition: External hardware device that takes electronic data from a computer or other device and generates a hard copy of it. They are commonly used to print text and photos.

metadata.title: Photocopiers, scanners
metadata.definition: Device that makes copies of documents and other visual images and stores them as a digital image, sends, or prints them.
metadata.includes: Xerox machine, FAX machine, document scanner

metadata.title: Document shredders
metadata.definition: Mechanical device used to cut material into strips or fine particle to destroy private, confidential, or otherwise sensitive documents.

metadata.title: Document handling equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Computer and peripheral equipment that is known but does not match codes from 7531 through 7533.
metadata.includes: toner; copying fluids

metadata.title: Office, banking, and retail equipment
metadata.definition: Machinery and equipment, other than those listed previously, which primarily function in the office, banking, or retail environment.
metadata.includes: Automated teller machines (ATM's); calculating machines and cash registers; mailing and metering machines
metadata.excludes: computer and peripheral equipment (752); audio and video equipment (75); vending machines (391); staplers (7154); agricultural shredders (312)

metadata.title: Office, banking, and retail equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Office, banking, and retail equipment with too little information to choose a code from 7541 through 7549.

metadata.title: Automated teller machines (ATM)
metadata.definition: Electronic banking outlet that provides basic transactions using a card and without the aid of a teller.
metadata.includes: ATM; cash machine; automated teller

metadata.title: Calculating devices, cash registers
metadata.definition: Mechanical or electronic devices used to perform the basic operations of arithmetic automatically and conduct financial transactions.
metadata.includes: Calculators; adding machine; sales register; till

metadata.title: Mailing and metering equipment
metadata.definition: Mechanical device used to imprint an amount of postage on a mailed item, functioning as a postage stamp, a cancellation and a dated postmark all in one.
metadata.includes: Franking machine; letter folding machine; sorting machine

metadata.title: Office, banking, and retail equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Office, banking, and retail equipment that is known but does not match codes from 7541 through 7543.
metadata.includes: Coin-counting machinery; dictating machines

metadata.title: Media, office and business equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Media, office and business machinery, equipment and supplies that are known but do not match codes from 7510 through 7549.

metadata.title: Writing and artistic equipment
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify tools, instruments, and equipment used for artistic, artisan, and musical undertakings.
metadata.includes: musical instruments; sewing notions; writing, drawing and art supplies; single sheet paper
metadata.excludes: containers (21); furniture and fixtures (22); tool chests (2211); machinery (3); mechanical jacks (344); parts and materials (4); hoisting accessories (45); machine, tool, and electric parts (46);  tarps (4251)

metadata.title: Writing and artistic utensils— unspecified
metadata.definition: Artistic equipment and supplies with too little information to choose a code from 7611 through 7619.
metadata.excludes: paint (434); ink and dye (1645); drawing tables (2224); blackboards and bulletin boards (226); modeling clay (4111); paint brushes (7199); knives (7124); laser pointers (7519)

metadata.title: Dividers, compasses, protractors
metadata.definition: Marking devices primarily used to draw large circles or arcs or to draw lines at a measured distance from an edge.
metadata.includes: divider calipers, trammel heads or points, compass

metadata.title: Pens, pencils, chalk, crayons
metadata.definition: Instruments and utensils used for writing or drawing.
metadata.includes: blackboard or marking chalk; charcoal, chalk or wax crayons; markers; pastels; wooden pencils; pens; fountain pens; gel pens and markers; mechanical pencils

metadata.title: Multiple types of writing and artistic utensils
metadata.definition: Combination of items from 2 or more codes from 7611 through 7619.

metadata.title: Writing and artistic utensils— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Artistic supplies, materials, and equipment that is known but does not match codes 7611 through 7618.
metadata.includes: canvasses and frames; erasers; easels; eraser guides; shields picture frames; hand seals and seal dies; stamps; ink pads; rubber stamps; textile printing screens; stencils; stickers; needlework & embroidery supplies & kits; art kit; craft supplies
metadata.excludes: paint (434); ink and dye (1645); glue and paste (433); paper, cardboard (4932)

metadata.title: Musical instruments
metadata.definition: All musical instruments and their associated parts and accessories, including music stands.

metadata.title: Musical instrument— unspecified
metadata.definition: All musical instruments and their associated parts and accessories with too little information to choose a code from 7621 or 7629.

metadata.title: Pianos, organs, keyboards
metadata.definition: Musical instruments with a keyboard.
metadata.includes: spinet; clavichord; pianoforte player piano; clavier; pinola

metadata.title: Musical instruments— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Electronic and non electronic musical instruments and their accessories and parts, except pianos, organs and keyboards.
metadata.includes: accordions; banjos; bassoons; bells; bugles; cellos; chimes; oboes; clarinets; ocarinas; cornets; octophones; cymbals; piccolos; drums; flutes; saxophones; French horns; synthesizers; guitars; sitars; trombones; harmonicas; trumpets; harps; ukuleles; harpsichords; vibraphones; mandolins; violas; marimbas; violins; wind chimes; xylophones; zithers; musical instrument accessories (e.g. reeds, mouthpieces,  stands, traps)

metadata.title: Sewing notions
metadata.definition: Sewing notions which are commonly used to produce hand-sewn articles.
metadata.includes: Safety pins; sewing needles; thimbles; knitting and crochet needles and accessories; fiber art equipment
metadata.excludes: hypodermic or medical needles (7411); thread, fabric, trim (4942); scissors (7125)

metadata.title: Athletic and outdoor equipment
metadata.definition: Codes in this major group classify indoor and outdoor recreation and athletic equipment.
metadata.includes: bats and balls; writing, drawing, and art supplies; camping equipment; gymnasium, playground, sports and exercise equipment
metadata.excludes: firearms and other law enforcement and self-defense equipment (78);  athletic clothing and footwear–excluding skis and skates (911); computer gaming systems and equipment (7529)

metadata.title: Athletic and outdoor equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Recreation and athletic equipment  with too little information to choose a code from 771 through 779.

metadata.title: Ball, stick, and throwing sports equipment
metadata.definition: Any equipment used in ball and throwing sports or other forms of play.
metadata.includes: baseballs; basketballs; bowling balls; hockey pucks; frisbees; golf clubs; tennis rackets; lacrosse sticks; baseball bats; boomerangs
metadata.excludes: furniture and fixtures related to ball sports (e.g. pool table, ping pong table) (2)

metadata.title: Gymnasium and exercise equipment
metadata.definition: Equipment that is used for exercising, weight lifting, and gymnastics as well as equipment used on playgrounds.
metadata.includes: jump ropes; gym mats; exercise machines used for fitness or physical therapy; exercise cycles; jogging machines; rowing machines; treadmills; weight-lifting equipment; boxing equipment; swings; sliding boards; sandboxes; playgrounds, jungle gyms; rock climbing walls; obstacle courses; hurdles; roller skates and blades; skateboards; stilts
metadata.excludes: zip lines (392); skate park structures; ski jumps (6389)

metadata.title: Skis, snow sports equipment
metadata.definition: Equipment related to snow sports.
metadata.includes: snow skis; ski poles; bobsleds; sleds; toboggans; luges; snowboards; ice skates; curling equipment
metadata.excludes: safety glasses or goggles (9225); snowmobiles (8614); skiing apparel (911)

metadata.title: Water sports equipment
metadata.definition: Water sports equipment used in diving, surfing, swimming, and other related water sports, except apparel and oxygen tanks.
metadata.includes: diving masks, snorkels; surfboards; nose plugs; sailboards; flotation devices; kick boards; life preservers; water skis; paddles; oars
metadata.excludes: apparel such as bathing suits or wet suits (911); oxygen tanks (2124); fishing equipment (777); water vehicles (83);  PPE ear plugs (9226); SCBA equipment (9232)

metadata.title: Camping equipment
metadata.definition: Equipment that is used for camping outdoors.
metadata.includes: portable lanterns; air mattresses; canteens; sleeping bags; mess kits; tents and accessories; hammocks
metadata.excludes: tarps (4251); flashlights (7199); backpacks (2162), cots (2221); camp knives, cutting tools (712)

metadata.title: Equestrian equipment
metadata.definition: Horse riding goods and equipment.
metadata.includes: saddles; riding crops; reins; horseshoes

metadata.title: Fishing equipment
metadata.definition: Equipment used for either commercial or recreational fishing purposes.
metadata.includes: lobster and crab pots; fishing tackle (e.g. hooks, rods, reels); gaffs, harpoons

metadata.title: Hunting and trapping equipment— except firearms
metadata.includes: archery equipment (hunting and recreational); traps, mousetraps; camouflage equipment
metadata.excludes: crab pots, fish traps (777); knives (7124); camouflage apparel (911)

metadata.title: Athletic and outdoor equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Recreation and athletic equipment that is known but does not match codes from 770 through 778.
metadata.excludes: respirators (923); personal protective devices (92); mopeds (8444); bicycles (851); powered golf carts (8612); go carts (8619)

metadata.title: Firearms, law enforcement, and other self-defense equipment
metadata.definition: Equipment such as firearms that is used by law enforcement or as a means or self defense.

metadata.title: Firearms, law enforcement, and other self-defense equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Equipment such as firearms that is used by law enforcement or as a means or self defense with too little information to choose a code from 7810 through 789

metadata.title: Firearms, air-powered guns
metadata.definition: All types of firearms and their parts.
metadata.includes: pistols; handguns; revolvers; ammunition; rifles; shotguns; bombs; torpedoes; grenades; missiles; rockets; artillery shells; air-powered and paint ball guns
metadata.excludes: nail guns (7154); recreational archery equipment (778); bullets, pellets (7821); taser, stun and electroshock guns (7832); knives (7124)

metadata.title: Firearms, air-powered guns— unspecified
metadata.definition: Firearm with too little information to choose a code from 7811 through 7819.
metadata.includes: unknown type of gun

metadata.title: Handguns
metadata.definition: Short-barreled firearm that can be held and used with one hand.
metadata.includes: Pistol, handgun, revolver

metadata.title: Long guns
metadata.definition: Portable, long-barreled firearm designed for accurate shooting, typically to be held with both hands.
metadata.includes: musket, rifle, shotgun

metadata.title: Air-powered guns
metadata.definition: Weapon that fires a projectile by means of air pressure.
metadata.includes: BB guns; pneumatic weapon; air gun, paintball guns

metadata.title: Firearms, air-powered guns— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Firearm that is known but does not match codes from 7811 through 7813.

metadata.title: Weaponized explosive devices and ammunition— unspecified
Ammunition
metadata.definition: Devices intended Projectiles which are fired by a weapon.
metadata.includes: bullets; pellets; shot; shrapnel from explosives and bullets; rubber bullets

metadata.title: Explosive devices
metadata.definition: Device intended for use as a weapon that relies on the exothermic reaction of an explosive material to provide a violent release of energy.
metadata.includes: Bomb; Molotov cocktail; grenade; shell; missile; rocket

metadata.title: Weaponized explosive devices and ammunition— n.e.c.
Other law enforcement and self-defense equipment
metadata.definition: Equipment, except firearms, that is used by law enforcement or as a means or self defense.

metadata.title: Other law enforcement and self-defense equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Equipment, except firearms, that is used by law enforcement or as a means or self defense with too little information to choose a code from 7831 through 7839.

metadata.title: Batons, clubs, blunt weapons
metadata.definition: Thick, heavy stick used as a weapon by authorities.
metadata.includes: Batons; nightsticks; billy clubs; maces; blackjacks; bludgeons; clubs; brass knuckles

metadata.title: Tasers, stun guns
metadata.definition: Handheld device used to immobilize a person without causing serious injury, typically by administering an electric shock.

metadata.title: Tear gas, mace, pepper spray
metadata.definition: Chemical weapon that causes severe eye and respiratory pain, and skin irritation.
metadata.includes: bromobenzyl cyanide; ethyl iodoacetate; chloroacetophenone; lacrimogenic gas

metadata.title: Handcuffs, restraint devices
metadata.definition: Restraint devices designed to secure an individual's wrists in close proximity to each other.

metadata.title: Law enforcement and self-defense equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Equipment, except firearms, that is used by law enforcement or as a means or self defense that is known but does not match codes from 7831 through 7834.
metadata.includes: police shields; sling shots; flexible weapons; nun chucks; whips; chain weapons

metadata.title: Firearms, law enforcement, and other self-defense equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Equipment such as firearms that are used by law enforcement or as a means or self defense that are known but do not match codes from 7810 through 784.
metadata.includes: electromagnetic devices; riot foam

metadata.title: Other Tools, instruments, equipment
metadata.definition: Tools, instruments, and equipment that are known but do not match codes in groups 71 through 78.
metadata.includes: candles; clothes hangers; lighters, matches; combs; soap dispensers; curlers; fly swatters; tobacco pipes; geographical globes; umbrellas
metadata.excludes: containers, furniture, and fixtures (2); tool chests (2211); machinery (3); mechanical jacks (344); hoisting accessories (45); machine, tool, and electric parts and accessories (46); tarps (4521); building materials (42)

metadata.title: Drug and tobacco paraphernalia
metadata.definition: Items and paraphernalia used exclusively for the administration of recreational drugs or other substances.
metadata.includes: pipes; vaping devices; e cigarettes; bongs; hookah; rolling papers
metadata.excludes: hypodermic needles used for illicit drug use (7411)

metadata.title: Toys, games
metadata.definition: Items designed for use in play, especially for children.
metadata.includes: blocks; electronic toys; dolls

metadata.title: Other tools, instruments, equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Tools, instruments, and equipment that are known but do not match other detail codes in Division 7.
metadata.includes: candles; clothes hangers; lighters, matches; combs; soap dispensers; curlers; fly swatters; geographical globes; umbrellas; cash, coins; personal razors; toothbrushes; other toiletries
metadata.excludes: containers, furniture, and fixtures (2); tool chests (2211); machinery (3); mechanical jacks (344); hoisting accessories (45); machine, tool, and electric parts and accessories (46); tarps (4521); building materials (42)

metadata.title: VEHICLES
metadata.definition: This division classifies air, rail, water, roadway, and non-roadway vehicles, as well as some industrial vehicles and tractors. In order to be included in this Division, the vehicle must serve the primary purpose of transporting people or materials or to pull other machinery (tractors). Vehicles for all modes of public, private, work-related, and recreational transportation are included in this division. Mobile and truck mounted machinery and equipment which are primarily used for agricultural, construction, logging, mining, manufacturing, and other processing purposes are classified in Division 3, Machinery.
metadata.includes: Air vehicles; rail vehicles and unattached rail cars; water vehicles; motorized highway vehicles; nonmotorized highway vehicles; off-road vehicles including powered plant and industrial vehicles; tractors
metadata.excludes: Agricultural and garden machinery (31); construction, logging, and mining machinery (32); material and personnel handling machinery (34); ski lifts and amusement rides (39); unattached vehicle and mobile equipment parts (47); vehicle doors, lift gates, tailgates (47); Unattached vehicle windshields and windows (47)

metadata.title: Vehicle— unspecified
metadata.definition: Select this code when the broad type of vehicle is unknown and a more specific vehicle code from 810 to 899 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Aircraft
metadata.definition: This major group classifies fixed- and rotary-winged aircraft. The aircraft may be designed for public, private, or military use. An air vehicle code should be selected as either the source or secondary source whenever the event is an aircraft incident.
metadata.includes: Powered fixed wing aircraft; powered rotary wing aircraft; non-powered aircraft; spacecraft

metadata.title: Aircraft— unspecified
metadata.definition: Select this code when a more specific aircraft code from 8110 to 819 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: "Plane" or "aircraft" with no further details

metadata.title: Airplanes—powered fixed wing
metadata.definition: This source group classifies aircraft which is supported by a fixed wing structure. The airplane can be jet engine or propeller powered.
metadata.includes: Turbine or piston type aircraft, planes

metadata.title: Airplane—powered fixed wing, unspecified
metadata.definition: Powered fixed wing aircraft which cannot be determined whether they are jet or propeller powered.

metadata.title: Airplane—jet or turbine engine
metadata.definition: Powered fixed wing aircraft equipped with jet engine(s) that propel the airplane forward.
metadata.includes: Turbojets, turboprops, commercial jet, jet aircraft

metadata.title: Airplane—propeller-driven or piston engine
metadata.definition: Powered fixed wing aircraft which relies on propellers to fly the plane.
metadata.includes: Light aircraft, general aviation aircraft, and crop dusters unless specified otherwise

metadata.title: Airplane—powered fixed wing, n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Powered fixed wing aircraft that rely on neither jet nor propeller engines to fly.

metadata.title: Helicopters, powered rotary wing aircraft
metadata.definition: Aircraft which is supported by a rotary wing. The aircraft can be rotary wing only or a combination of rotary wing and jet propulsion.
metadata.includes: Helicopters; air ambulances, unless otherwise specified; tiltrotor aircraft

metadata.title: Aircraft—nonpowered
metadata.definition: This source group classifies aircraft that glide or float without some type of power source, such as jet propulsion, propellers, or hot air.
metadata.includes: Nonpowered gliders; parachutes
metadata.excludes: Jets (8111), propeller airplanes (8112), helicopters (812), hot air balloons, dirigibles (819)

metadata.title: Aircraft—nonpowered, unspecified
metadata.definition: Nonpowered aircraft when a more specific code from 8131 to 8139 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Glider, hang glider—nonpowered
metadata.definition: Aircraft whose free flight does not depend on an engine.
metadata.includes: Nonpowered glider; hang glider; rogallo wings

metadata.title: Parachute
metadata.definition: A cloth canopy which fills with air when dropped from a height and allows a person or heavy object attached to it to descend slowly to the ground.
metadata.includes: Paraglider

metadata.title: Aircraft—nonpowered, n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Nonpowered aircraft when a the specific type of aircraft is known, but does not match descriptions of codes 8131 to 8132.

metadata.title: Aircraft, n.e.c.
metadata.definition: This category classifies aircraft which are not previously classified in group 81.
metadata.includes: Hot-air balloons, dirigibles, manned spacecraft

metadata.title: Rail vehicles
metadata.definition: This major group classifies mass transit and freight vehicles operating above and below ground.

metadata.title: Rail vehicle— unspecified
metadata.definition: Select this code when a more specific rail vehicle code from 821 to 829 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: "Train" without further information

metadata.title: Streetcar, trolley, light rail
metadata.definition: Rail vehicles that run on tracks along public urban streets.
metadata.includes: Cable car

metadata.title: Subway, elevated train
metadata.definition: Light passenger rail vehicles that run on tracks underground or elevated over urban roadways providing mass transit.
metadata.includes: Metro; tube; U-Bahn; T; Septa
metadata.excludes: Passenger and commuter trains running on heavy rail lines (8232)

metadata.title: Heavy rail vehicles
metadata.definition: Heavy locomotive engines or rail cars. These typically travel between cities and may transport passengers or cargo.
metadata.includes: Train, locomotive, rail car, passenger train, freight train

metadata.title: Heavy rail vehicles— unspecified
metadata.definition: Heavy locomotive engines or rail cars when a more specific code from 8231 to 8239 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Freight train
metadata.definition: Heavy trains transporting freight.
metadata.includes: Mixed freight; unit trains; intermodal trains

metadata.title: Passenger train— heavy
metadata.definition: Heavy trains transporting passengers.
metadata.includes: Passenger and commuter trains running on freight line tracks

metadata.title: Unattached locomotive
metadata.definition: Train engine that provides the power for a train of rail cars that is not couple to a train or car(s).
metadata.includes: Engine

metadata.title: Unattached rail car
metadata.definition: Any rail car designed for freight or passenger transport, that is separate from the locomotive or train configuration.
metadata.includes: Caboose; box car; tanker car; flat bed car

metadata.title: Heavy rail vehicles— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Heavy train cars or engines that are specified but do not meet descriptions of codes 8231 to 8234.

metadata.title: Construction, cleaning, maintenance machine— rail mounted
metadata.definition: Rail-mounted machinery for construction, cleaning, and maintenance of rail lines.
metadata.includes: Highway vehicles outfitted with railroad wheels while running on rails; hi-rail truck

metadata.title: Industrial, mining vehicle— rail mounted
metadata.definition: This specific code includes all rail vehicles used to transport goods and materials within an industrial or mine site.
metadata.excludes: heavy rail passenger train (8232), freight train (8231)

metadata.title: Rail vehicle— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: This category classifies rail vehicles which are not previously classified in codes 821 to 825.
metadata.includes: Handcar

metadata.title: Water vehicles
metadata.definition: This major group classifies water vehicles used for transporting people or materials, for commercial fishing, or for recreational purposes. Use code 835 if it is unknown whether a yacht was under sail or motor power at the time of the incident.
metadata.includes: Powered and nonpowered water vessels; water taxis
