metadata.excludes: Barge-mounted cranes, floating cranes (3423/); manure agitator boat (33)

metadata.title: Water vehicle— unspecified
metadata.definition: Water vehicles when a more specific code from 831 to 839 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Barge
metadata.definition: A flat-bottomed boat for carrying freight, typically on canals and rivers, either under its own power or towed by another.
metadata.includes: Car ferry

metadata.title: Commercial fishing vessel
metadata.definition: Boats of any type that are used for commercial fishing purposes.
metadata.includes: Commercial fishing boats

metadata.title: Tugboat, towboat
metadata.definition: A powerful boat used for towing larger vessels, especially in harbor.

metadata.title: Cargo ship, freighter, passenger liner
metadata.definition: Large water vessels either carrying cargo, goods, or passengers.
metadata.includes: Cruise ships; reefer; container ship; bulk carrier; aircraft carrier; battle ship

metadata.title: Motorboat, motorized yacht
metadata.definition: Smaller motorized watercraft used for a variety of purposes.
metadata.includes: Water taxi, commuter ferry; police or fire boat; boat; chartered tour boats; Coast Guard cutter

metadata.title: Sailboat
metadata.definition: Sail-powered water vessels of any size.
metadata.includes: Sail-based yacht; replica sailing ships

metadata.title: Rowboat, kayak, canoe, raft
metadata.definition: Small watercraft powered by either hand or foot paddles (pedals).
metadata.includes: Pedal boat; stand up paddleboard

metadata.title: Water vehicle— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: This category classifies water vehicles which are not previously classified in codes 831 to 837.
metadata.includes: Jet skis, Hovercraft

metadata.title: Roadway vehicles— motorized
metadata.definition: This major group classifies vehicles which are operated primarily on highways and other public roadways and used for transportation, hauling, delivering, and emergencies. If it is unknown whether a vehicle is being used to carry passengers or cargo, use the first code in the list.
metadata.includes: Automobiles; buses; motorcycles, mopeds, dirt bikes; motor homes, recreational vehicles; trucks; vans
metadata.excludes: Nonmotorized highway vehicles such as bicycles (851); horse-drawn carriages (852); off-road vehicles such as forklifts (8621); tractors (863); golf carts (8612); truck-mounted machinery or equipment not in transport (Division 3)

metadata.title: Roadway vehicle— motorized, unspecified
metadata.definition: Use this code for descriptions of roadway 'vehicles' where no other information can be determined about the vehicle type.

metadata.title: Emergency and security vehicles
metadata.definition: This source group classifies vehicles that are licensed and equipped for emergency response or law enforcement purposes. Personal vehicles that are used for emergency response are excluded from group 841.
metadata.excludes: personal vehicles used in emergency response (code to the appropriate vehicle type from groups 842 through 849)

metadata.title: Emergency vehicle— unspecified
metadata.definition: Emergency vehicles where a more specific code from 8411 to 8419 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Police patrol vehicle
metadata.definition: Any type of passenger vehicle used for police activities.
metadata.includes: Squad car, cruiser, SUV, truck; unspecified prisoner transport; unmarked police vehicles

metadata.title: Ambulance
metadata.definition: Trucks or vans equipped with lifesaving equipment for emergency medical patient transport.
metadata.includes: Truck or van equipped as an ambulance

metadata.title: Police or prisoner transport van, bus
metadata.definition: Small trucks or vans used to transport larger groups of people, including prisoner transport or teams of police or protective service responders.
metadata.includes: Paddy wagon, prisoner transport

metadata.title: Fire truck, other emergency equipment truck
metadata.definition: Trucks mounted with specialized firefighting or emergency response equipment.
metadata.includes: Hazmat trucks; emergency equipment haulers; SWAT vans; hook and ladder trucks

metadata.title: Police motorcycle
metadata.definition: Motorcycles used for police and emergency activities.

metadata.title: Emergency vehicles— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Emergency vehicles which are not previously classified in codes 8411 to 8415.
metadata.includes: Police bike; armored truck
metadata.excludes: Military vehicles (89); police Segway (non-roadway vehicle) (8619); Police horse (5154)

metadata.title: Trucks with mounted machinery, equipment
metadata.definition: Mobile equipment, truck mounted machinery and other utility-type trucks involved in primarily transportation incidents. Only select a code from 842 if the narrative mentions that the truck had mounted machinery.
metadata.excludes: Unspecified trucks without mention of mounted machinery or equipment (8430); trucks hauling machines or equipment that is not attached (select appropriate code from 843); 5th wheel, gooseneck trailer (select appropriate code from 843); armored trucks (8439); pickup trucks with snow plows (8431)

metadata.title: Trucks with mounted machines, equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Mobile equipment, truck mounted machinery and other utility-type trucks where a more specific code from 8421 to 8429 cannot be determined.
metadata.excludes: trucks carrying machines or equipment that is not attached (select appropriate code from 843); 5th wheel, gooseneck trailer (select appropriate code from 843)

metadata.title: Tow truck
metadata.definition: Trucks equipped to move disabled, improperly parked, impounded, or otherwise indisposed motor vehicles. They typically include a tilting flat bed and winch apparatus to load vehicles.

metadata.title: Dump trucks
metadata.definition: Trucks equipped with a body that tilts or opens at the back for unloading bulk loose materials.
metadata.includes: Semi truck with dump trailers; pick- up trucks with dump trailers
metadata.excludes: Off-road oversized dump trucks (i.e. mining and quarrying dump trucks) (8439)

metadata.title: Garbage trucks
metadata.definition: Trucks equipped with a body is specially designed to collect and transport solid waste.
metadata.includes: garbage truck; recycling truck, refuse truck

metadata.title: Cement and concrete mixer trucks
metadata.definition: Trucks specially equipped with rotating drums to mix and agitates wet concrete as well as concrete pouring equipment.

metadata.title: Boom truck, cherry picker
metadata.definition: Trucks equipped a lift to elevate persons or materials.
metadata.includes: Truck-mounted bucket or basket hoists, aerial lifts, cherry pickers (when involved in incidents that are classified as Transportation); Utility bucket trucks; boom truck; truck mounted cherry-pickers; truck mounted tree removal

metadata.title: Trucks with other mounted machinery, equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Trucks with mounted machinery, equipment  which are not previously classified in codes 8421 to 8425.
metadata.includes: equipment; road salting trucks without further information on truck type
metadata.excludes: Fire trucks (8414); mobile equipment not designed for travel on public roadways (e.g. construction earth moving equipment, agricultural tractors, etc.) (Division 3); Truck mounted equipment NOT involved in a Transportation event (e.g. Struck by object or equipment) (Division 3)

metadata.title: Trucks
metadata.definition: This source group classifies light and heavy trucks which are commonly used for transporting, hauling, and delivering materials or equipment. Trucks with permanently mounted machinery or equipment should be coded in 842. Trucks equipped with snow plows or other removable accessories should be classified in 843 according to the type of truck (i.e. a pick up truck with a plow should be coded as 8431, pickup truck).
metadata.includes: trucks without mention of permanently mounted machinery or equipment; trucks with detachable accessories such as snow plows or trailers
metadata.excludes: Trucks with permanently mounted machinery or equipment (842) street sweepers (893); forklifts (8621); tractors (863*); hand trucks (2133); passenger vans (8445); non truck-mounted aerial lifts (3435); SUVs (8443); armored personnel carriers, tanks, Humvees (89); fire trucks (8414); tow trucks (8421);

metadata.title: Trucks— unspecified
metadata.definition: Motorized freight hauling and utility trucks where a more specific code from 8431 to 8439 cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: Truck, unspecified (of unknown size); trucks of unknown size without mention of mounted machinery or equipment.

metadata.title: Pickup truck
metadata.definition: A light duty truck consisted of a driver cab and an enclosed cargo back or open truck bed. Trucks equipped with snow plows or other accessories should be classified according to the type of truck (i.e. a pick up truck with a plow should be coded as 8431, pickup truck).
metadata.includes: Dually pickup trucks; service body utility pickup truck; pickup truck with snow plow

metadata.title: Straight trucks, box trucks
metadata.definition: Straight or box trucks are smaller trucks for which the cab and the bed are on the same frame together. They are typically used to deliver goods or as work trucks.
metadata.includes: Box trucks, straight trucks, delivery trucks, food trucks
metadata.excludes: SUVs, sports utility vehicles (8443); pickup trucks used for deliveries (8431); passenger vans (8445)

metadata.title: Tanker trucks
metadata.definition: Trucks equipped with a trailer designed to transport bulk liquids. These are typically used for oil and gas transportation.
metadata.includes: Semi truck with tanker; oil tankers, gas tankers, compressed natural gas (CNG) trucks, chemical tankers, agricultural tankers, liquid food tankers, water tank trucks, compartmentalized tanker trucks

metadata.title: Other semi, tractor-trailer
metadata.definition: Trucks that are a combination of a tractor unit and one, or more, removable semi-trailers to carry freight. A semi-trailer attaches to the tractor with the use of a hitch.
metadata.includes: Flatbed trucks—except straight trucks, logging trucks, car haulers; terminal tractor, yard truck, shunt truck, ULD
metadata.excludes: Vehicle hitches and unattached trailing units (47)

metadata.title: Trucks— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Other heavy motorized freight hauling and utility trucks which are not previously classified in codes 8431 to 8434.

metadata.title: Passenger vehicles
metadata.definition: This source group classifies vehicles that are used primarily for transporting passengers. These types of vehicles typically have a gross vehicle weight ratings (GVWR) of less than 10,000 pounds. Vehicles for transporting goods and materials are in source group 843.
metadata.excludes: Heavy trucks (843), Medium weight trucks, pickup trucks (843)

metadata.title: Passenger vehicle— unspecified
metadata.definition: Light passenger vehicles where a more specific code from 8441 to 8449 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Taxi
metadata.definition: Any type of vehicle used to transport customers for a fare on an ad hoc basis. This includes traditional taxi companies and well as app-based services.
metadata.includes: Automobiles, vans, SUVs, and limos equipped for use as taxis; airport shuttles
metadata.excludes: Animal-powered taxi (85), Pedi cab (851); water taxi (835); air taxi (81); ride share vehicles (e.g. Uber, Lyft) (8442 or 8443)

metadata.title: Automobile
metadata.definition: Small passenger vehicles, typically with 2 to 4 doors. They are usually equipped to carry 2 to 5 passengers.
metadata.includes: Car, limousine, unspecified automobile or car; sedan; coupe; mini urban cars
metadata.excludes: Taxi (8441); police car (8411); rail car (8234); racecar (8613); armored car (8429)

metadata.title: Sports utility vehicle (SUV)
metadata.definition: Vehicles that combine elements of road-going passenger cars with features from off-road vehicles, such as raised ground clearance and four-wheel drive.
metadata.includes: 4-wheel drive vehicles, jeeps; station wagon or crossover vehicles; SUV limousines

metadata.title: Motorcycle, moped, dirt bike
metadata.definition: Motorized two-wheel vehicles that are considered road worthy.
metadata.includes: Motor bike, motor scooter; road trikes, 3-wheelers

metadata.title: Vans, passenger and utility
metadata.definition: All sizes of vans, equipped to transport passengers (except those used as buses and taxis), haul cargo or to use as a utility work vehicle.
metadata.includes: Minivan, full-sized passenger van; cargo vans, delivery vans
metadata.excludes: Courtesy airport van, taxi (8441); van-based bus (8446)

metadata.title: Bus
metadata.definition: Medium or large vehicles designed to transport large numbers of passengers.
metadata.includes: Transit bus, tour or charter bus, school bus, intercity bus; van-based bus

metadata.title: Motor home, RV
metadata.definition: Recreational vehicles or DOT approved mobile home consisting of a motor vehicle or trailer which includes living quarters designed for accommodation.
metadata.includes: Recreational vehicle (RV)
metadata.excludes: Mobile home, semi-permanent trailer home, parked tiny house, manufactured home (626)

metadata.title: Passenger vehicle— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Passenger vehicles which are not previously classified in codes 8441 to 8447.
metadata.includes: Hearse

metadata.title: Roadway vehicle— motorized, n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Roadway vehicles which are not previously classified in codes 840 to 8449.

metadata.title: Animal or human- powered vehicles
metadata.definition: This major group classifies animal or human- powered highway vehicles, as well as other non-motorized highway vehicles.
metadata.includes: Horse-drawn carriages; bicycles—road and mountain, pedal cycles
metadata.excludes: Motorized highway vehicles (84); nonpowered plant and industrial vehicles and containers (213); horses being ridden (5154)

metadata.title: Animal or human-powered vehicle— unspecified
metadata.definition: Animal- or human-powered vehicle where a more specific code from 851 to 859 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Bicycle, pedal cycle
metadata.definition: Human powered vehicle consisting of a steerable frame and wheels propelled by foot pedals.
metadata.includes: Unicycle; Pedi cab; bicycle rickshaw; road bicycle; mountain bicycle

metadata.title: Horse-drawn carriage, buggy
metadata.definition: Passenger vehicle drawn by horses.
metadata.includes: Horse drawn sleigh
metadata.excludes: Horse-drawn plows that are not ridden (31)

metadata.title: Animal-powered wagon
metadata.definition: Material hauling vehicle drawn by animals.
metadata.includes: Horse drawn wagon or other farm equipment; dog sled

metadata.title: Animal or human-powered vehicle— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Animal or human-powered vehicles which are not previously classified in codes 851 to 853.

metadata.title: Off-road and industrial vehicles—powered
metadata.definition: This major group classifies off-road vehicles that are primarily used for transportation in nonroadway areas, such as on farms, industrial premises, and recreational areas.
metadata.includes: All terrain vehicles (ATVs); powered golf carts; snowmobiles; motorized scooters, except for mobility scooters
metadata.excludes: Motorcycles, dirt bikes (8444); jeeps, four-wheel drive trucks, sports utility vehicles (8443); mountain bicycles (851); wheelchairs and mobility scooters (Division 7)

metadata.title: Off-road or industrial vehicle—powered, unspecified
metadata.definition: Off-road or industrial vehicle where a more specific code from 8610 to 869 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Off-road passenger vehicles—powered
metadata.definition: This source group classifies vehicles used for transporting passengers in nonroadway areas.

metadata.title: Off-road passenger vehicle—powered, unspecified
metadata.definition: Off-road passenger vehicle where a more specific code from 8611 to 8619 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: All-terrain vehicle (ATV)
metadata.definition: All-terrain vehicles (ATVs) are motorized off-highway vehicles having a seat designed to be straddled by the operator and handlebars for steering control.
metadata.includes: Quad; three-wheeler; four-track, four-wheeler; UTV

metadata.title: Golf cart, personnel transport cart
metadata.definition: Small vehicles designed to carry two or more persons and/or small amounts of cargo over non-roadway areas.

metadata.title: Racecar
metadata.definition: Automobiles or other vehicles built or modified for racing or entertainment purposes.
metadata.includes: Monster truck; stunt car

metadata.title: Snowmobile
metadata.definition: Vehicles designed  for traveling over snow. They typically include runners in the front and caterpillar tracks in the rear.

metadata.title: Off-road passenger vehicles—powered, n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Off-road passenger vehicles which are not previously classified in codes 8610 to 8614.
metadata.includes: Segways ™
metadata.excludes: Wheelchairs and mobility scooters (Division 7), mopeds and motor scooters (8444)

metadata.title: Industrial vehicles, material hauling and transport—powered
metadata.definition: This source group classifies forklifts, powered industrial carriers, and industrial vehicles which are used for carrying and transporting heavy materials in primarily nonroadway areas.
metadata.includes: Forklifts; powered industrial carriers; airport utility vehicles; powered pallet jacks
metadata.excludes: Tractors (863); product assembly robots (Division 3); Non-powered pallet jacks, carts, dollies, wheeled containers and carriers (213)

metadata.title: Industrial vehicle, material hauling and transport—powered, unspecified
metadata.definition: Powered material hauling and transport industrial vehicles where a more specific code from 8621 to 8629 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Forklift, order picker, platform truck—powered
metadata.definition: Powered industrial trucks equipped with prongs that can vertically lift materials and move them over short distances.
metadata.includes: Tow motors, lift trucks, skid steers with forklift attachment; turret truck

metadata.title: Industrial carrier— powered
metadata.definition: Small vehicles used to transport materials short distances in non-roadway areas, such as warehouse aisles.
metadata.includes: Container, lumber, stacker, and straddle carriers; burden carrier
metadata.excludes: Non-powered pallet jacks, carts, dollies, wheeled containers and carriers (213)

metadata.title: Pallet jack—riding
metadata.definition: Motorized equipment that can either be ridden or walked behind to allow lifting and moving of heavier and stacked pallets.
metadata.includes: Electric pallet trucks, walkies, single or double pallet jacks, or power jack
metadata.excludes: Hand pallet jacks, nonpowered (2132); jacks, other than pallet (344)

metadata.title: Airport utility vehicle— powered
metadata.definition: Non-roadway vehicles specially outfitted for use in airports and airplane runways
metadata.includes: Powered luggage trucks or trains, powered airplane tugs, drivable airport stairs
metadata.excludes: Non-powered pallet jacks, carts, dollies, wheeled containers and carriers (213)

metadata.title: Oversized industrial hauler
metadata.definition: Oversized and jumbo vehicles designed to haul materials on industrial premises, such as a mine or quarry.
metadata.includes: Mine and quarry dump trucks

metadata.title: Industrial vehicle, material hauling and transport—powered, n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Powered material hauling and transport industrial vehicles which are not previously classified in codes 8620 to 8625.

metadata.title: Agricultural tractors
metadata.definition: Tractors are vehicles used to pull agricultural or other equipment (e.g. plows, cultivators, and mowers) or to power stationary devices such as saws and winches.
metadata.includes: Wheeled tractors; crawlers tractors, or caterpillars, which move on treads.
metadata.excludes: Construction tractors (321); Powered take off (PTO) (4743); agricultural machinery (31)

metadata.title: Off-road or industrial vehicle—powered, n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Powered off-road and industrial vehicles which are not previously classified in codes 8610 to 863.

metadata.title: Other vehicles
metadata.definition: This category includes vehicles that are not elsewhere classified, including military vehicles.

metadata.title: Military vehicle— except tanks
metadata.definition: Military vehicles designed for a variety of purposes, including transport personnel and equipment in combat zones.
metadata.includes: Humvee; Joint Light Tactical Vehicle; armored personnel carrier

metadata.title: Tank
metadata.definition: Armored fighting vehicle equipped with heavy firepower, strong armor, and caterpillar tracks for off-road maneuverability.

metadata.title: Street sweeping and cleaning machinery
metadata.definition: Mobile equipment designed to clean streets with vacuums and/or sweeper brushes.

metadata.title: Vehicle— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Other vehicles which are not previously classified in codes 810 to 893.
metadata.includes: Zamboni (ice and floor cleaning)

metadata.title: SAFETY AND ENVIRONMENTAL FACTORS AND CONDITIONS
metadata.definition: This division classifies sources of injuries and illness factors and conditions that affect the safety of a worker's immediate and extended environment. It includes apparel worn by the worker, including Personal protective equipment (PPE) and safety conditions and practices in the workplace. It also includes broader environmental influences, such as weather and natural phenomena. Codes from Division 9 should typically not be coded as the Source of injury, except when no other code applies. More frequently, these will be used as Secondary source codes.
metadata.includes: worn apparel; Personal protective equipment (PPE) and other safety equipment; conditions specific to roadways; environmental and elemental conditions

metadata.title: Safety and environmental factors and conditions— unspecified
Apparel, laundry, linens
metadata.definition: This major group classifies finished textiles including worn clothing, apparel and accessories as well as clean or dirty laundry or linens.
metadata.excludes: Textiles and unfinished materials, e.g. Fur, wool, and leather (5212); protective apparel, safety clothing (921); installed window coverings (2232); rugs, floor coverings (2231)

metadata.title: Apparel, clothing— except safety
metadata.definition: This source group classifies apparel that are either worn by the injured worker at the time of incident or directly contributed to the incident.
metadata.includes: worn apparel; apparel used as a weapon or means of violence
metadata.excludes: Textiles and unfinished materials, e.g. Fur, wool, and leather (5212); protective apparel, safety clothing (921);  safety glasses and goggles (9225); Winter gloves, mittens (9217); disposable and medical grade gloves (9211); unworn clothing designated as laundry (913)

metadata.title: Apparel, clothing— except safety, unspecified
metadata.definition: Clothing and footwear where a more specific code from 9111 to 9119 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Shoes, socks, footwear
metadata.definition: Footwear, hosiery, and other items to be worn on the feet.
metadata.includes: Boots, slippers, sandals, safety shoes

metadata.title: Hats, caps, headwear
metadata.definition: Hats, caps, millinery, and other accessories for the head.
metadata.includes: hair net; medical and surgical caps; sun hat; baseball cap; hijab, head scarf

metadata.title: Belts
metadata.definition: Belts, suspenders, and other items meant to hold up pants.
metadata.includes: Suspenders
metadata.excludes: Tool belts, backpacks (216), safety belts, seat belts (4732); lifting belts (9223)

metadata.title: Neckties, scarves, neckwear
metadata.definition: Clothing accessories meant to be worn around the neck.
metadata.includes: Bandanas

metadata.title: Eye glasses, sunglasses
metadata.definition: Accessories designed to be worn around the eyes.
metadata.includes: Contact lenses

metadata.title: Clothing
metadata.definition: Any clothing covering the trunk, upper, and lower extremities
metadata.includes: blouses, shirts, pants, coveralls; underclothes; uniforms; scrubs
metadata.excludes: Protective clothing and PPE apparel (921); footwear, socks (9111)

metadata.title: Apparel, clothing— except safety, n.e.c.
metadata.includes: Jewelry, ID badge lanyards; watches

metadata.title: Towels, linens, bedding
metadata.definition: This source includes bed and bath items like sheets and towels.
metadata.includes: Sheets, towels, blankets, comforters, tablecloths, napkins, face cloths, wash cloths
metadata.excludes: Beds, mattresses, and box springs (2221); air mattresses (775); sheet, towels, linens, and bedding designated as laundry (913)

metadata.title: Laundry
metadata.definition: Clothing that is not being worn and placed for laundry; sheets, towel, linens, and bedding not being used and placed for laundry
metadata.excludes: Laundry storage containers, bags or hampers of laundry (211)

metadata.title: Personal protective equipment (PPE)
metadata.definition: This division classifies apparel, worn protective equipment (PPE) and other forms of safety equipment that were involved in an injurious incident. The item(s) must have either been in use by the injured worker and failed to protect them or have directly contributed to the injury.
metadata.includes: worker's clothing caught in machinery; worker hangs self with belt; worker tripped over safety marker; worn footwear rubbed blister on worker's foot
metadata.excludes: failure to use/wear required safety apparel or equipment (92); injuries due to laundry or textiles not worn by worker (49X)

metadata.title: Personal protective equipment (PPE)— unspecified
metadata.definition: Apparel, worn protective equipment (PPE) and other forms of safety equipment that were involved in an injurious incident where there is not enough detail to determine a more detailed code from 921 to 923.

metadata.title: Protective apparel
metadata.definition: Specialized apparel worn by workers as protection of their body in hazardous work environments.

metadata.title: Protective apparel— unspecified
metadata.definition: Protective apparel with too little information to choose a code from 9211 through 9219.

metadata.title: Disposable and medical gloves
metadata.definition: Protective glove made of latex, nitrile or other material for medical use and protection against infectious agents.
metadata.includes: medical gloves; nitrile; latex; vinyl; cleaning gloves

metadata.title: Arc rated and insulating apparel, gloves
metadata.definition: Clothing or other apparel that is designed to protect against electrical and arc exposures
metadata.includes: arc rated clothes, faceguards, gloves

metadata.title: Steel-toed footwear
metadata.definition: Shoe that has a protective reinforcement in the toe which protects the foot from falling objects or compression, usually combined with a mid sole plate to protect against punctures from below.
metadata.includes: safety shoe or boot; steel capped boot

metadata.title: Hard hat, helmet
metadata.definition: Headwear used in workplace environments to protect the head from injury due to falling objects, impact with other objects, debris, rain, and electric shock.
metadata.includes: construction helmet; safety hat

metadata.title: HAZMAT suit, gown
metadata.definition: Impermeable whole-body garment worn as protection against hazardous materials.
metadata.includes: decontamination suit; surgical gown

metadata.title: High-visibility reflective clothing, accessories
metadata.definition: Clothing or accessories that is highly luminescent or reflective or of  a color that is easily discernible from any background.
metadata.includes: Hi-Viz clothing; fluorescent vest; safety vest

metadata.title: Gloves, handguards— except disposable, electric insulating
metadata.definition: Gloves or handguards made of rubber, leather or other material  that provide protection from cold, caustic material, and sharp edges or materials.
metadata.includes: work gloves; rubber gloves; mesh gloves; winter gloves, mittens
metadata.excludes: medical gloves (9211); arc flash gloves, insulating gloves (9212)

metadata.title: Protective apparel— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Protective apparel that is known but does not match codes from 9211 through 9217.
metadata.includes: athletic supporters or cups; lead apron or thyroid guard

metadata.title: Other protective equipment
metadata.definition: Specialized equipment, other than apparel, worn by workers as protection.

metadata.title: Other protective equipment— unspecified
metadata.definition: Specialized equipment, other than apparel, worn by workers as protection with too little information to choose a code from 9221 through 9229.

metadata.title: Kneepads, shin guards
metadata.definition: Protective covering worn on the knees or legs to decrease soft tissue discomfort or injury
metadata.includes: Kneepad and shin guards

metadata.title: Fall protection equipment
metadata.definition: Worn equipment that provides fall protection by allowing for the safe stopping of a person already falling. Fall protection should be used when workers are working at heights of 6 feet or greater.
metadata.includes: lifelines; lanyards; safety belts and harnesses; fall arrest harness

metadata.title: Back support belt
metadata.definition: Device worn to reduce pressure on the spine and provide protection during lifting.
metadata.includes: lumbar support belt; industrial support belt

metadata.title: Human exoskeleton equipment
metadata.definition: Wearable mobile machine powered by a system of electric motors, pneumatics, levers, hydraulics, or a combination of technologies that allow for limb movement with increased strength and endurance
metadata.includes: powered armor or suit; exoframe; hard suit; exosuit; exoskeleton equipment used as medical devices

metadata.title: Eye and face protection
metadata.definition: Equipment worn to protect the face in hazardous work environments.
metadata.includes: safety glasses or goggles; face shield; welder mask

metadata.title: Hearing protection
metadata.definition: Equipment worn to protect hearing from loud environments.
metadata.includes: ear plugs; earmuffs; wax balls

metadata.title: Other protective equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Specialized equipment, other than apparel, worn by workers as protection that is known but doe not match a code from 9221 through 9226.
metadata.includes: crampons, climbing spurs

metadata.title: Respirators
metadata.definition: Devices worn over the mouth or whole face that remove contaminants from the air or supply breathable air in oxygen deficient environments.

metadata.title: Respirators— unspecified
metadata.definition: Devices worn over the mouth or whole face that remove contaminants from the air or supply breathable air in oxygen deficient environments where a more specific code from 9231 to 9239 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Air filtering respirators
metadata.definition: Devices that remove gases, vapors, aerosols, or a combination of contaminants from the air through the use of filters, cartridges, or canisters.
metadata.includes: dust masks; medical grade masks; N95, N99, N100 masks; KN94, KN95 masks; filtering facepiece; cartridge filtering masks

metadata.title: Supplied air respirators, SCBA
metadata.definition: Respiratory protection equipment that supplies air in environments where the ambient air is harmful for breathing or not present (such as underwater). These devices provide breathable air from an alternate air source, such as a cylinder or air hose. The air is delivered to the worker through a hood, face mask or mouth piece.
metadata.includes: air supplied masks; self-contained breathing apparatus (SCBA); air helmets; airline respirator; fire fighting breathing apparatus

metadata.title: Cloth facemask
metadata.definition: Non-medical grade facemasks used for prevention of respiratory illness transmission.
metadata.includes: COVID masks

metadata.title: Respirators— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Devices worn over the mouth or whole face that remove contaminants from the air or supply breathable air in oxygen deficient environments that do not meet descriptions of 9231 to 9233.
metadata.includes: Emergency escape mouthpiece respirators

metadata.title: Personal protective equipment (PPE)— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Apparel, worn protective equipment (PPE) and other forms of safety equipment that were involved in an injurious incident that does not meet descriptions of codes from 921 to 923.

metadata.title: Safety controls and equipment— except PPE
metadata.definition: Common safety intervention strategies with a focus on selected types of engineering controls and administrative controls. These codes should be used if mentioned as either being present, but unsuccessful when an injury occurred or when authoritative documents state that they were required but absent from the work environment.

metadata.title: Safety controls and equipment— except PPE, n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Safety intervention strategies with a focus on selected types of engineering controls and administrative controls when a more specific code from 931 to 9339 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Fire extinguishers
metadata.definition: Portable emergency device that discharges a jet of water, foam, gas, or other material to extinguish a fire.

metadata.title: Wheel chocks, blocks
metadata.definition: Devices placed in front of or behind vehicles or mobile equipment to keep them from rolling unexpectedly.

metadata.title: First aid station equipment
metadata.includes: first aid stations, defibrillators, eye washing stations

metadata.title: Engineering controls
metadata.definition: Engineering controls includes devices and systems that serve as barriers between workers and known, proximate hazards. This group also includes equipment and systems designed to provide emergency relief in case of a harmful event. These codes should be selected when either the physical object or the communication protocol directly causes an injury or exposure or failed to alert workers to a hazardous condition, exacerbating an exposure.

metadata.title: Engineering controls— unspecified
metadata.definition: Engineering controls includes devices and systems that serve as barriers between workers and known, proximate hazards or provide emergency relief in case of a harmful event where a more specific code from 9321 to 9329 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Machine vent hoods
metadata.definition: Equipment used to exhaust harmful gases and heat produced by machinery away from areas occupied by workers.

metadata.title: Rollover protective structure (ROPS)
metadata.definition: A system or structure intended to protect equipment operators and motorists from injuries caused by vehicle overturns or rollovers.
metadata.includes: rollbars, roll cages

metadata.title: Robotic arm perimeters
metadata.definition: Areas of restricted access around the area in which robotic equipment moves.

metadata.title: Machine guards
metadata.definition: Barriers and guards to prevent contact with equipment and machinery
metadata.includes: hand guards; machine railings; cage guards

metadata.title: Sprinkler systems, dust suppression
metadata.definition: Interior systems designed to discharge water and fire suppressants in the case of an emergent fire.
metadata.includes: building sprinkler systems; dust suppression systems

metadata.title: Engineering controls— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Engineering controls includes devices and systems that serve as barriers between workers and known, proximate hazards or provide emergency relief in case of a harmful event that do not meet descriptions of codes 9321 to 9325.
metadata.includes: trench support systems including benching, sloping, shoring, and shielding

metadata.title: Autonomous or robotic system failure
metadata.definition: Failure or malfunction of computer systems designed to replace human operators on all types of vehicles and machinery. This includes machines that are capable of performing or controlling unsupervised mechanical movements or environmental control functions.
metadata.includes: failure of automated machinery that can perform simple tasks, but without complex computer control (i.e. printer malfunction)

metadata.title: Communicable disease safety protocols
metadata.definition: Protocols and practices put in place by either the employer or government authority to maintain work environment safety from infectious disease. These codes should be selected when case information documents a condition that occurs as a result of a violation of these protocols.

metadata.title: Communicable disease safety protocols— unspecified
metadata.definition: Protocols and practices put in place by either the employer or government authority to maintain work environment safety from infectious disease when a more specific code from 9341 to 9349 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Facility sanitization protocols
metadata.definition: Cleaning and sanitation protocols implemented to reduce spread of infection.
metadata.includes: hospital and doctor's office cleaning protocols; enhanced cleaning protocols

metadata.title: Infection screening protocols
metadata.definition: Protocols designed to assess the health of individuals entering a specific area.
metadata.includes: temperature checks; symptom screenings

metadata.title: Employee vaccination protocols
metadata.definition: Employer-required vaccination protocols for prevention of infectious disease.
metadata.includes: Required flu shots; required COVID-19 vaccines; vaccines required for health care workers; vaccines required for educators
metadata.excludes: Vaccinations suggested, but not required by the employer (1571)

metadata.title: Face masking protocols
metadata.definition: Employer required face masking and face covering protocols
metadata.includes: Required use of cloth masks, N95 or equivalent; face shields
metadata.excludes: Suggested, voluntary masking protocols; Breach of requirement to use respirators for non-infectious contaminants (939); Ineffective use of respirator (923)

metadata.title: Employee work area in close proximity to others
metadata.definition: Employee work environment requires frequent in-person interaction or contact with coworkers, patients, wards, clients, or members of the public.
metadata.includes: shared work station or area; shared equipment; in-person patient, student, ward or client care resulting in infectious disease

metadata.title: Communicable disease safety protocols— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Protocols and practices put in place by either the employer or government authority to maintain work environment safety from infectious disease that do not meet descriptions of codes 9340 to 9345.
metadata.includes: plexiglass barriers

metadata.title: Hazard communication and signage
metadata.definition: Devices and systems used to detect and communicate hazards to workers within a particular area of premise. These codes should be selected when either the physical object or the communication protocol directly causes an injury or exposure or fails to alert workers to a hazardous condition, exacerbating an exposure. It should also be chosen if the narrative documents a situation in violation of safety protocols.
metadata.includes: Injuries directly caused by signage (e.g. hearing damage caused by alarm, tripping over safety marker); Injuries resulting from failure to heed or implement hazard communication when case information specifies

metadata.title: Hazard communication and signage— unspecified
metadata.definition: Devices and systems used to detect and communicate hazards to workers within a particular area of premise where a more specific code from 9351 to 9359 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: "Lock out/ tag out" communication systems
metadata.definition: Procedures used to ensure that equipment is shut down and inoperable until maintenance or repair work is completed. It typically involves a system of signs and locks or clips to prevent machinery from being powered on.

metadata.title: Safety markers
metadata.definition: Devices that are placed on roads or other surfaces to temporarily redirect road and foot traffic in a safe manner or block off a hazardous area.
metadata.includes: pylons; witches' hats; road cones; highway cones; safety cones; channelizing devices; construction cones; caution tape

metadata.title: Lights, signs— hazard and safety
metadata.definition: Lighted or non lighted signs indicating a potentially hazardous area or signaling need for additional caution.
metadata.includes: construction zone lights or signs; flares; stop lights; pedestrian crossing lights

metadata.title: Environmental exposure monitors
metadata.definition: Devices and systems designed to detect hazardous environments and conditions and alert workers to those hazards.
metadata.includes: fire alarms; CO monitors; security alarms; building alarms; particulate matter monitors; radiation monitors (e.g. Geiger counters)

metadata.title: Hazard communication and signage— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Devices and systems used to detect and communicate hazards to workers within a particular area of premise that does not meet descriptions of codes 9350 to 9354.
metadata.includes: Material safety data sheets; civil defense sirens (e.g. storm sirens, air raid sirens); fog horns

metadata.title: Safety practices, administrative controls
metadata.definition: Protocols and practices put in place by either the employer or government authority to maintain work environment safety. These codes should be selected when case information documents a condition in violation of these protocols.

metadata.title: Safety practices, administrative controls— unspecified
metadata.definition: Protocols and practices put in place by either the employer or government authority to maintain work environment safety when a more specific code from 9361 to 9369 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Workers engaging in horseplay
metadata.definition: Rough or boisterous play or pranks that occur at the workplace. These codes should be selected when case information documents that horseplay contributed to the harmful event.
metadata.includes: joking that includes physical contact; playing around; racing; grabbing; foolish vehicle operation; social pressure to participate in unsafe acts; harassment; unauthorized contests
metadata.excludes: Intentional violence towards self or other worker(s) (57)

metadata.title: Permissible exposure limits exceeded
metadata.definition: Legal limits for exposure of an employee to a chemical substance or physical agent such as high level noise. Select this code if case information documents that this condition contributed to a harmful event.
metadata.includes: Prolonged radiation exposure; hazardous atmosphere exposure

metadata.title: Workers engaging in team lift
metadata.definition: Protocol for lifting heavy or bulky items by sharing the load between two or more people. Select this code when case information documents that team lifting activities contributed to the harmful event.

metadata.title: Irregular or extended work shift
metadata.includes: Shift limits exceeded; on-call work shifts

metadata.title: Safety practices, administrative controls— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Protocols and practices put in place by either the employer or government authority to maintain work environment safety that do not meet descriptions of codes 9360 to 9363.
metadata.includes: worker declines to use or removes provided safety equipment, apparel

metadata.title: Safety protocols and equipment— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Safety intervention strategies with a focus on selected types of engineering controls and administrative controls that do not meet descriptions of codes in group 93.

metadata.title: Factors and conditions specific to vehicles, mobile equipment
metadata.definition: This major group classifies factors and conditions that have particular impact for the operation of motor vehicles and mobile equipment.
metadata.excludes: Weather and atmospheric conditions (952); health conditions of vehicle operator (561)

metadata.title: Vehicle or mobile equipment failure
metadata.definition: This source group classifies failure or malfunction of the vehicle or equipment occupied by the injured worker
metadata.includes: autonomous vehicle software failure or breach; tire blow out; engine failure; electrical failure
metadata.excludes: Failure of other vehicles (not occupied by injured worker) that were involved in the crash; failure of non-mobile equipment

metadata.title: Avoiding objects in path of travel
metadata.definition: This source group classifies instances where the driver was attempting to avoid objects in the roadway or path of travel and lost control of the vehicle without impacting that object.
metadata.excludes: Collision with object in roadway (select appropriate code for impacted object; pedestrian or animal struck cases)

metadata.title: Avoiding objects in path of travel— unspecified
Avoiding pedestrian, live animal in path of travel
metadata.includes: motorists outside of their vehicles

metadata.title: Avoiding moving object in path of travel
metadata.includes: vehicles being driven in normal operation; runaway vehicles in non-normal operation

metadata.title: Avoiding stationary object in path of travel
metadata.includes: stopping quickly for traffic jam ahead

metadata.title: Operator impaired— except injured or ill worker
metadata.definition: This group classifies the physical status of vehicle and equipment operators in the injured or ill worker's environment, not the injured or ill worker themselves.
metadata.excludes: Injured worker was operating vehicle/machine while impaired by drugs (15) … impaired by medical condition (561)

metadata.title: Operator impaired— Unspecified
metadata.definition: Use this code when a worker is injured as a result of another person who is operating equipment while impaired, but it is unknown whether the injured worker was an occupant of the impaired worker's vehicle at the time of the incident.

metadata.title: Operator impaired— Vehicle occupied by injured worker
metadata.definition: Use this code when the injured worker is the passenger of a vehicle or machine being operated by another impaired person.

metadata.title: Operator impaired— Other vehicle not occupied by injured worker
metadata.definition: Use this code when the injured worker is struck by a vehicle or machine being operated by another impaired person. The injured worker may be a pedestrian or the occupant of another vehicle.

metadata.title: Environmental and elemental conditions
metadata.definition: This major group classifies conditions of the environment such as air pressure, temperature, and other atmospheric conditions, as well as events such as natural disasters. Select weather and atmospheric conditions or geological events (floods, earthquakes, avalanches) as the source of injury when that is the only possible source identified.
metadata.includes: Includes: air pressure; avalanche; mudslide; earthquake; fire, flame, smoke; flooding; environmental temperature extremes; weather and atmospheric conditions; noise, sun, welders’ flash; indoor air quality

metadata.title: Environmental and elemental conditions— unspecified
metadata.definition: Environmental and elemental conditions where a more specific code from 9510 to 9599 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Avalanche, mudslide, rockslide
metadata.definition: Avalanche or other slide involving earth, ground, or rocks.
metadata.includes: Rockslide; mudflow

metadata.title: Earthquake
metadata.definition: Earthquake or aftershock of earthquakes
metadata.includes: Aftershocks of earthquakes

metadata.title: Wildfire
metadata.definition: Uncontrolled fire in an area of combustible vegetation

metadata.title: Flooding— except weather related
metadata.definition: Displacement of a large volume of water, generally from an ocean or a large lake.
metadata.includes: dam burst;

metadata.title: Disasters— except weather, n.e.c.
metadata.includes: volcanic eruption; drought conditions

metadata.title: Weather, atmospheric conditions
metadata.definition: This source group classifies weather and atmospheric conditions. If rain or high winds are a result of a hurricane or tornado, code the hurricane or tornado as the source. When the injury results from a weather condition, but is inflicted by another specific source, code the specific source. For example, if high winds result in blowing sawdust which irritates the employee’s eyes, the sawdust should be coded as the source.
metadata.excludes: Air pressure (9531); avalanche (9511); earthquake (9512); hot and cold environmental temperature extremes (954*); sun (9551); waves, surges, rough seas—except those occurring during tornado, hurricane, typhoon (9527); ice chips, cubes, and blocks (9521); ice on freezer floor (9521)

metadata.title: Weather, atmospheric conditions— unspecified
metadata.definition: Weather and atmospheric conditions where a more specific code from 9521 to 9529 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Ice, sleet, snow, hail
metadata.definition: Frozen precipitation generated outside of  a storm.
metadata.includes: Icicles; ice on sidewalk; blizzard

metadata.title: Tornado, hurricane, typhoon
metadata.definition: Storm or atmospheric condition that typical has strong winds and/or precipitation.
metadata.includes: Tropical storm, dust storm, ice storm, flooding due to storms

metadata.title: Rain
metadata.definition: Liquid precipitation generated outside of a storm.
metadata.includes: flooding due to rain
metadata.excludes: Rain due to tornado, hurricane, typhoon (9522)

metadata.title: Fog, mist, haze
metadata.definition: Fog, mist, haze the occurs naturally as part of the weather and environment.

metadata.title: High winds, gusts, turbulence
metadata.definition: Winds, gusts, turbulence that occur outside of a storm.
metadata.includes: airplane turbulence
metadata.excludes: Winds, gusts, turbulence due to tornado, hurricane, typhoon (9522)

metadata.title: Lightning
metadata.definition: Lightning that originates in the atmosphere.

metadata.title: Waves, surges, rough seas
metadata.definition: Waves and other rough seas that affect the worker or maritime vessel.
metadata.includes: Tsunami
metadata.excludes: Flooding due to tornado, hurricane, typhoon (9522); flooding due to precipitation (9523)

metadata.title: Multiple weather and atmospheric conditions
metadata.includes: Rain and fog combined

metadata.title: Weather, atmospheric conditions— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Weather and atmospheric conditions that do not match descriptions of codes 9521 through 9528.

metadata.title: Environmental and elemental pressure
metadata.definition: This source group classifies abnormal environmental air pressure conditions as well as pressurized air. Low pressure refers to rarefied air at extreme elevations.

metadata.title: Environmental pressure— unspecified
metadata.definition: Air pressure where a more specific code from 9531 to 9539 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Atmospheric pressure—high or low
metadata.definition: The effects of altitude and being underground (but not underwater).

metadata.title: Water pressure—high or low
metadata.definition: Effects or low or high water pressure that might lead to decompression sickness.

metadata.title: Pressurized air—blast
metadata.definition: Blasts of air, typically for a device designed for that purpose like a blower or sand blaster.
metadata.includes: Air/particles from an air compressor or sand blaster

metadata.title: Pressurized water—blast
metadata.definition: A pressurized blast of water typically from an instrument designed for that purpose like a hose or pressure washer.

metadata.title: Oxygen deficient environment
metadata.definition: Environments, typically associated with confined spaces, where oxygen has been displaced by other gases, resulting in asphyxiation.

metadata.title: Environmental pressure— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Air pressure that does not match descriptions of codes 9531 through 9535.

metadata.title: Temperature extremes—environmental
metadata.definition: This source group classifies atmospheric and environmental temperature extremes—either indoors or outdoors. Codes in this category are used primarily in instances of heat stroke, heat exhaustion, hypothermia, etc.
metadata.includes: Environmental (outdoor or indoor) heat, environmental (outdoor or indoor) cold
metadata.excludes: fire, flame, smoke (955*); ice, sleet, snow (9521); hot or cold objects

metadata.title: Temperature extremes—environmental— unspecified
metadata.definition: Temperature extremes - environment where a more specific code from 9541 to 9542 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Cold—environmental
metadata.definition: Cold from the environment like from frigid outdoor temperatures or in an indoor food locker.

metadata.title: Heat—environmental
metadata.definition: Heat from high outdoor temperatures or from a hot indoor area like proximate to a blast furnace.

metadata.title: Light, radiation, noise
metadata.definition: This source includes the energy waves that compose natural and artificial light, noise, and radiation. Note that, with the exception of code 9551, Sun,  this source group refers to the energy waves themselves and not to the items that produce them.

metadata.title: Light, radiation, noise— unspecified
metadata.definition: Light, radiation, and noise where a more specific code from 9551 to 9559 cannot be determined.

metadata.title: Sun
metadata.definition: Light and glare generated by the sun that affects the worker's vision.
metadata.includes: Sun/light that impairs vision

metadata.title: Fire, flame
metadata.definition: Fire, flame, and other hot parts of combustion.

metadata.title: Welders’ flash
metadata.definition: Flash from the process of welding.

metadata.title: Lasers
metadata.definition: Intense beams of light (or other electromagnetic radiation) created by stimulating emission of photons from excited atoms or molecules.
metadata.includes: Lasers emitted by drilling and cutting equipment, laser levels and surveyors, surgical equipment; bar code readers; laser pointers

metadata.title: Other ultraviolet (UV) light
metadata.definition: This code is used for ultraviolet electromagnetic radiation (with wavelength from 10 nm to 400 nm).
metadata.includes: light coming from tanning bed lights; sun lamps; mercury and xenon arc lamps, such as those used in fluorescence microscopy
metadata.excludes: Sunlight (9551), welder's flash (9553); the source of the UV light (select appropriate source code)

metadata.title: Particle Radiation
metadata.definition: This code is used for radiation of energy by means of fast-moving subatomic particles.
metadata.includes: nuclear radiation

metadata.title: Noise
metadata.definition: Noise and other sound on the audible spectrum.
metadata.includes: sonic boom, industrial noise

metadata.title: Light, radiation, noise— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: Light, radiation, and noise that do not match descriptions of codes 9551 through 9557.
metadata.includes: microwaves; x-rays; lamp light; fluorescent lights; strobing lights

metadata.title: Other environmental and elemental conditions
metadata.definition: This source group includes other environmental conditions that have not been covered in a previous category.

metadata.title: Source, secondary source— unspecified
metadata.definition: Use this code when it is known that there was a source based on the selected event, but it cannot be determined what that item is. For example, This code would apply if it is known that a worker struck against an object, but the specific object is unknown and the broad source Division of the object (i.e. machinery, vehicle, structure) cannot be determined.
metadata.includes: use this code for unknown container contents

metadata.title: Secondary source not applicable
metadata.definition: Use this code when there is no applicable Secondary Source on a case. For example, in a single vehicle crash with no contributing factors, the source would be coded as the vehicle, but, since no other secondary source is applicable to the case, code 999 would be selected.

metadata.title: Known exposure, no or unknown incidence of injury or illness
metadata.definition: Use this code when an at-work exposure to disease or harmful substances has occurred, but the worker has not manifested signs of injury or illness. This code is also applicable when source documents report only the initial details of the incident but medical follow-up information is unknown.
metadata.includes: Known exposure to infectious disease

metadata.title: Other source, secondary source— n.e.c.
metadata.definition: This code is used for sources that are known, but are not classified anywhere else in the source code structure. This code is also used for multiple objects or substances that are not in the same division, but only if the two objects or substances equally contribute to producing the injury.
metadata.includes: Cigarettes, cigars, vaping devices
